##
## "Miscellaneous"
##

@NODE Miscellaneous "Miscellaneous"
                         "Miscellaneous" Information

* The cursor (arrow) keys on the keyboard work in all scrollable lists.
  Up/down-arrow keys scroll by one item, alt-up/down-arrow keys scroll by
  one page,and shift-up/down-arrow keys scroll to the top/bottom of the
  lists. Similarly the Home/End/PgUp/PgDn and cursor key on the numeric
  key-pad can also be used to scroll through lists.

* When adding children or adding a spouse to a family group, more rigorous
  relationship checking is carried out (compared to previous versions).
  Incest is still possible (!), but biological impossibilities are not.

* See @{" Loading/Converting Old Databases " LINK Conversion}

* Conversion of old-style databases does NOT "bring across" any last name
  picklists from old-style databases.

* Memory usage is typically 50% less than earlier versions of Scion (very
  data dependent).

* Database files are now typically 20% - 30% bigger than the old-style
  ones. The exact size increase is very dependent on the actual data in
  the database.

* The minimum "usable" font size is 6 "point". With anything smaller, the
  "tool" area gadgets (on the right-hand side of the windows) will overlap.

* With very large databases, display lists can take several seconds to
  appear while they are constructed and sorted. With more than 200
  people/families in a database, a "self-cancelling" "Sorting..." message
  will appear. See also @{" List sorting " LINK Sorting}.

* With very large databases it can take a couple of seconds to actually
  quit the programme. This is due to all the memory cleanups and releases.
  With more than 200 people in the database, a "self-cancelling"
  "Freeing resources..." message will appear.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Installation"
##

@NODE Installation "Installation"
                               Installation

Programme Requirements:
----------------------
	Kickstart/Workbench v2.04 (or later). Version 2.10 (or later)
	required for locale support (alternative languages).

	A minimum of 1 Mbyte of RAM. 4 Mbytes of RAM is recommended.
	Hard-disk drive STRONGLY recommended.

Installation:
------------
The preferred method is to use the supplied "Install" programme.

However, it is relatively easy to install Scion "by-hand"....

(1) Create a drawer where you want Scion installed.
(2) Drag or copy the Scion programme into this drawer.
(3) The startup picture displayed when you run Scion is stored in a file
    named 'ScionLogo'. This file should be copied to the same drawer as the
    programme. If you prefer, you can replace this file with a picture file
    of your own (it MUST be in IFF-ILBM format), or you can delete it
    altogether. NOTE: This file has no icon - use the
    "Window/Show/All Files" menu on the Workbench to see the file.
(4) Dearchive the "Scion.Guide" help file from "ScionSupport.lha" and store
    it in the same drawer as the programme.

    THIS COMPLETES THE MINIMUM INSTALLATION.

(5) If you want to create your own ARexx programmes, you should dearchive
    the 'ScionRexx.Guide' file from the "ScionSupport.lha" archive. This
    file contains information on all the ARexx commands supported by Scion.
(6) The default language of Scion is English. If there are additional
    (non-English) support files supplied, you should dearchive the files
    for your preferred language(s) from "ScionSupport.lha".

    The non-English files should be installed in two locations:

    (a) The "localisation" catalog files are -
                'ScionProgDir/catalogs/language/scion5.catalog'

        where - 'ScionProgDir' is the (full) name of the Scion programme
		 drawer, and
              - 'language' is the non-English language (eg 'deutsch'), and
              - 'scion5.catalog' is the non-English "localisation" file.

        Simply create the 'language' drawers for the languages you want
	and copy the appropriate 'scion5.catalog' files to these drawers.

    (b) The non-English help (.guide) files are -
                'ScionProgDir/guides/language/Scion.Guide'

        where - 'ScionProgDir' is the (full) name of the Scion programme
		 drawer, and
              - 'language' is the non-English language (eg 'deutsch'), and
              - 'Scion.Guide' is the non-English help file.

        Simply create the 'language' drawers for the languages you want
	and copy the appropriate 'Scion.Guide' files to these drawers.

        SPECIAL NOTE: If there is not a 'Scion.Guide' file in your
	        preferred language, the (default) English help file should
		remain in the 'guides/english' drawer (or in the same
		drawer as the programme). Then the English help file will
		be available instead.

(7) If you want to create your own non-English translations, you can
    use the files contained in the 'Translators' archive.
    NOTE: Please contact the author (Robbie Akins - <rakins@bclnz.co.nz>)
          before beginning a translation. It is possible that a
	  translation to your language is already under development!
(8) The archive "ScionARexx.lha" contains a large number of Scion ARexx
    support programmes supplied by Scion users.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Running Scion on the Workbench"
##
@NODE UseWB "Running Scion on the Workbench"
Starting with Scion v5.08, it is possible to run the programme on the
Workbench (or default public screen). This is achieved in one of two ways -

(1) From the Workbench icon

    There are two icon TOOLTYPES that Scion responds to -

    USEPUBLICSCREEN - include this TOOLTYPE to make Scion open its
                      windows on the Workbench (or default public screen)

                      When this TOOLTYPE is in use, "zoom" gadgets are added
		      to both the Personal and Family Windows. This allows
		      you to shrink the windows while running on the
		      Workbench (or default public screen). See also
		      Project menu @{" Iconify " LINK MenuIconify} option.

    FORCEPALETTE    - By default (and if you're running Scion under
		      Amiga OS 3.0+), Scion will do its best to make the
		      sex colours correct. That is, males displayed in
		      blue, females in red and 'unknown sex' in yellow.
		      However, this is NOT always entirely successful and
		      depends very largely upon how many colours your
		      Workbench (or default public screen) can display.

		      NOTE: These "best" colours ONLY apply to text. The
		            colours of the images in the various buttons
			    are NOT affected.

                      If the default colours are not satifactory, you can
		      FORCE Scion to use its preferred sex colour scheme
		      (assuming your screen can display at least 8 colours)
		      by including the FORCEPALETTE TOOLTYPE.

		      See also note below.

(2) From the CLI

    The command template is -

    U=USEPUBLICSCREEN/S,F=FORCEPALETTE/S,database

    EG. To run Scion on the Workbench (or default public screen), and to
        force it to use Scion's preferred colours, issue the command
	'Scion U F mydatabase', where 'U' is the accepted abbreviation
	for 'USEPUBLICSCREEN', 'F' is the accepted abbreviation for
	'FORCEPALETTE' (see also note below), and 'mydatabase' is the
	name of your Scion database file.

RESTRICTIONS
============
(1) Because Scion has no control over the size of the Workbench (or default
    public) screen, it is possible that the Scion windows will be too tall
    for the screen. You will need to select a 'shorter' screen font using
    the standard Amiga 'Font' preferences programme.

(2) When opening Scion on the Workbench (or default public screen), the
    display of the opening Scion 'logo' screen is suppressed. This is
    NOT a bug!

(3) Certain screen 'behaviour' options and colour-scheme options are not
    available when running Scion on the Workbench (or default public screen).

(4) The FORCEPALETTE option is only recognised when the USEPUBLICSCREEN
    option is used.

SPECIAL NOTE ON 'FORCEPALETTE' OPTION
=====================================
This option will temporarily modify colours 4-7 of your Workbench (or
default public screen) palette. Unlike some other "naughty" programmes
(such as 'IBrowse'), the original Workbench (or default public screen)
colours are restored when Scion exits. Generally this option will have
minimal impact on your Workbench (or default public screen) colours - the
main observable impact will usually be restricted to MagicWB icons (and
similar "images").
@ENDNODE

##
## "Loading/Converting Databases"
##
@NODE Conversion "Loading/Converting Databases"
                    Loading and Converting Databases

If your database was saved with a version of Scion EARLIER than Version 5,
then read @{" Loading/Converting Old Databases " LINK Pre5Conversion}.

If your database was saved with Scion Version 5 (or later), you can @{" ignore " LINK IgnoreThis}
this section.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Loading/Converting Old Databases"
##
@NODE Pre5Conversion "Loading/Converting Old Databases"
                    Loading and Converting Old Databases
		    ====================================

This section ONLY applies to databases created with PRE-VERSION 5 versions
of Scion. Current users of Scion Version 5+, CAN IGNORE THIS SECTION.

If you are trying to load a database (created with an earlier version of
Scion) into Scion Version 5+ for the first time, please read the following
sections VERY CAREFULLY.

                               -- 1 ---

If you have used the recommended "12 Feb 1987" type date format in your
database AND your native language is English, then just load your old
database into Scion Version 5+. A file "RAM:ScionErrorLog" (if generated)
will contain any error messages from the conversion of an old-style database
into a new-style database.  You will be advised if this file is created,
and be given an opportunity to view it using the internal "Notes Viewer"
(or your own selected notes viewer if defined).

                               -- 2 ---

If you have used a 'numeric' date format such as "12/2/1987" instead of
the recommended date format, then you will need to convert these dates into
the recommended "12 Feb 1987" format. To help you do this, run the supplied
ARexx programme 'FixDate.rexx' using your pre-version 5 Scion. This will
convert all 'numeric' dates to the recommended format, but will leave other
dates containing alphabetic characters (such as "About 1987") unchanged.

All converted month abbreviations will be in ENGLISH!

When the conversion is complete, save your database using a different name
(just in case) and then, if your native language is English, load the
'converted' database into Scion Version 5+ as described in section 1.

                               -- 3 ---

If your native language is NOT English then, once all the dates are in the
recommended "12 Feb 1987" format (see section 2 above), it is STRONGLY
recommended that your current "locale" is set to your native language, even
if there is not currently a catalog available for Scion in that language.
Scion will attempt to use the date abbreviations defined in this "locale".

Then try loading your database into Scion Version 5+.

Except for the special case of the SUMOI language (Finnish), a mixture of
English months and your native language months (as a result of doing any
"numeric date conversion" - see section 2 above) should not cause a problem.

WARNING FOR SUOMI (FINNISH) USERS: If you have had to perform a "numeric
date conversion" (as described in section 2) be aware that the third month
will be converted to "Mar" (for "March"). As "Mar" is the Suomi abbreviation
for "November", Scion will get confused!

You will need to manually change any "Mar" (for "March") abbreviations
to "Maa" (Suomi for "March") BEFORE attempting to load your database into
Scion Version 5+.

Finnish (Suomi) users should read @{" CONVERSION WARNINGS " LINK ConvertWarn}.

                               -- 4 ---

If it is not possible to use your preferred "locale", or you have NOT used
the month abbreviations common to your preferred language, it is STRONGLY
recommended that, using your EARLIER version of Scion (NOT this new version),
you convert the dates in your database into English using the supplied
"translate.rexx" arexx programme, and THEN load the TRANSLATED database into
Scion V5 with the current locale SET TO ENGLISH. "Translate.rexx" will only
translate your dates into English - it won't modify any other data. This
translation only needs to be done once when you convert an "old-style"
database, and you can then "revert" to using your preferred locale language.

        ###########################################################

          NON-ENGLISH USERS SHOULD REFER TO @{" CONVERSION WARNINGS " LINK ConvertWarn}

        ###########################################################

                               -- 5 ---

When loading database files created with earlier versions of Scion or
ArJay, a file "RAM:ScionErrorLog" (if generated) will contain any error
messages from the conversion of an old-style database into a new-style
database.  You will be advised if this file is created, and be given an
opportunity to view it using the internal "Notes Viewer" (or your own
selected notes viewer if defined).

See also @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}.

The only errors that will be reported are due to the much more rigorous
handling of dates in this new version. As long as you used the recommended
date format in earlier versions of Scion (that is, "dd mmm yyyy", for
example, "23 Jun 1947"), you will be okay.

If you used years such as "87" to mean "1987", this will be converted
literally - that is, to the actual year "87 AD". The century is important!

Similarly, if you used "date ranges" such as "1947-1952", Scion 5 is also
unable to handle the conversion of this style of date.

In all cases you should carefully check all dates against print-outs from
your earlier version of Scion. It is possible that some "unusual" dates
may not be correctly interpreted. Sorry, this will never happen again!

Databases only need to handle the "date conversion" once. Scion 5 uses a
completely new (language independent) format for dates.

SUGGESTIONS
-----------
(1) Where an event date is known to be within a range (such as between 1876
and 1879), enter the FIRST date in the appropriate date field, and make
a note in the "comments" field about the possible range.

(2) Where the day and month (but not the year) of an event is known, either
estimate the year and mark the date as 'circa', or record the partial date
in the 'comments' field.

See also @{" Dates " LINK DateField}.

@ENDNODE

##
## Conversion Warnings
##

@NODE ConvertWarn "Conversion Warnings for 'Old-Style' databases"
          Loading/Converting NON-ENGLISH "Old-Style" Databases
          ----------------------------------------------------

This section ONLY applies to databases created with PRE-VERSION 5 versions
of Scion in a language other than English. Current users of Scion Version 5+
and English users CAN IGNORE THIS SECTION.

=======     =======      =======      =======     =======      =======
WARNING     WARNING      WARNING      WARNING     WARNING      WARNING
=======     =======      =======      =======     =======      =======

MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ SECTIONS 3 & 4 OF @{" Loading/Converting Old Databases " LINK Pre5Conversion}.

Earlier versions of Scion supported the following languages - English,
Dansk, Franńais, Nederlands, Suomi, Deutsch, Italiano, Norsk and Svenska.
Unfortunately, catalogs for all these languages are not currently available
for this version of Scion.

This version of Scion will do its best to convert old-style database
dates with month abbreviations for all these languages. In fact, it will
also attempt conversion of databases in Bosanski, Czech, Polski, Espa±ol
and PortuguĻs. However, it is possible that some "date conversion errors"
may still occur.

You should check your converted database CAREFULLY for any unreported errors.

In the absence of a catalog in your language, all months will be displayed
in English.

In all cases you should carefully check all dates against print-outs from
your earlier version of Scion. Sorry, this will never happen again!

SPECIAL NOTE FOR SUOMI (FINNISH) USERS
--------------------------------------
Suomi databases use the abbreviation "Mar" for "November". To correctly
convert old-style Suomi databases using Suomi month abbreviations, MAKE
SURE THAT YOUR CURRENT LOCALE IS SUOMI, even if there is NOT a catalog
currently available for that language. If the locale is set to any other
language, any "Mar" (for November) dates will be interpreted INCORRECTLY
as "March".

Just be warned that, if you have done a "numeric date conversion", you will
need to manually change any "Mar" (for "March") abbreviations to "Maa"
(Suomi for "March"). Otherwise they will be incorrectly interpreted as
"November"!

SPECIAL NOTE FOR FRANŪAIS (FRENCH) USERS
----------------------------------------
If you have used French abbreviations for dates, MAKE SURE THAT YOUR
CURRENT LOCALE IS FRANŪAIS before you load your old-style database.

Unfortunately the program is not able to distinguish between "Apr"
(abbreviation for "Aprķs") and "Avr" (abbreviation for "Avril"). Scion 5
will trap this situation and report a "date conversion error" for dates
such as "Apr 1947" and "Apr Avr 1947". Preferably you should convert the
dates in your database into English using the supplied "translate.rexx"
arexx programme, and THEN load the TRANSLATED database into Scion V5
with the current locale SET TO ENGLISH. "Translate.rexx" will only
translate your dates into English - it won't modify any other data. This
translation only needs to be done once when you convert an "old-style"
database, and you can then "revert" to using your preferred locale
language.

As an alternative "work-around", it is suggested that you replace all
"Apr" (for "aprķs") by a '>' character BEFORE you attempt to load the file.
This character will always be correctly interpreted as "after". For
example, change "Apr Avr 1947" to "> Avr 1947" and "Apr 1947" to ">1947".
@ENDNODE

##
##
##

@NODE IgnoreThis "Ignore This Information"

Since you have already saved your database with Version 5 (or later) of
Scion, you can ignore this section. Just load your database!

@ENDNODE
##
## ARexx Introduction (Links to "ScionRexx.guide")
##

@NODE Searching "Searching"
                             "Searching"

The search capabilities of Scion Version 5 has been substantially improved.

See details on the @{" Personal Search " LINK PersonSearch} gadget and the @{" Family Search " LINK FamilySearch} gadget.

@ENDNODE

##
## ARexx Introduction (Links to "ScionRexx.guide")
##

@NODE AREXXIntro "ARexx Introduction"
                           ARexx Introduction

Scion Genealogist provides an ARexx interface for reading and modifying the
information contained in a database.

The default ARexx port name is SCIONGEN. If this name is not unique, or
more than one copy of Scion is running, the default ARexx port name will be
suffixed with a digit from 1 to 9. For example, SCIONGEN3. Therefore, up to
10 copies of Scion can be run, each with a unique ARexx port name.

To determine the actual ARexx port name in use, select the "Info" item in
the Project menu.

Click on this link -> @{" ARexx Interface " LINK "ScionRexx.guide/Main"} for more information.

It is possible that this link may return an error "Couldn't locate
ScionRexx.guide/Main". In this case, you will have to read the
"ScionRexx.guide" help file "off-line" using AmigaGuide or MultiView.

Sorry, but it's due to a limitation in the on-line help system.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK Overview ************************************************************

##
## "Programme Overview"
##

@NODE Overview "Programme Overview"
                           PROGRAMME OVERVIEW

      PREPARE!   PREPARE!   PREPARE!   PREPARE!   PREPARE!   PREPARE!

      Make sure that you have ALL possible information available
      before you start (with all the inter-personal and family relations
      sorted out). It will make things MUCH easier if you have a good
      idea what you are planning to do before you start!

The programme is based on two windows, the @{" Personal Details Window " LINK PersonalWindow}
and the @{" Family Details Window " LINK FamilyWindow}.

The Personal Details Window is used to enter and/or edit details about the
people that make up the database, and the Family Details Window is used to
establish the family relationships between these people.

Scion Genealogist has been written in a totally secular manner, has no
checking on sex (to allow for "unconventional" relationships), and has no
name checking (to allow for adopted children).  Also, the partners of a
family group (or marriage) are referred to as "Principal" and "Spouse".
Either partner can be the Principal.

Every person and family in the database is identified by a unique number:

@{" IRN - Individual Record Number " LINK IRN}      @{" FGRN - Family Group Record Number " LINK FGRN}

Details on the various people making up the database should be entered
FIRST and then the relationships between them can be established.

For example, when you have entered all the personal details for a group of
people, position the Personal Details Window to show the "husband". Now
click on the @{" Set 1st Marriage " LINK SetMarriage} gadget. This will create a new Family
Details Window with the "husband" established as the Principal.

To add his "wife", click on the @{" Set Spouse " LINK AddSpouse} gadget and select his wife
from the list of people that will be displayed. The Family Details Window
will now show the "husband" as Principal, and his "wife" as Spouse.

Finally, to add children to the family, click on the @{" Add Child " LINK AddChild} gadget and
select the children of the family from the list of 'parent-less' people
that will be displayed. Click on the "Accept" button, and the children
will be added to the family.

You have now established all the relationship details for the "husband",
the "wife" and the children. Continue in this way for all the other people
you have in your database.

See also @{" Hints, Tips & Questions " LINK Hints}.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK Personal Details Window Help *****************************************

##
## "Personal Details Window"
##

@NODE PersonalWindow "Personal Details Window"
                        PERSONAL DETAILS WINDOW

The Personal Details Window is used to enter and/or edit details about the
people that make up the database.

Details on the various people making up the database should be entered
FIRST and then the relationships between them can be established.

             @{" Entering and Editing Personal Information " LINK PersonalEdit}
             @{" Navigating Around the Personal Database   " LINK PersonalNavigation}
             @{" Personal Details Window Gadgets           " LINK PersonalGadgets}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Entering and Editing Personal Information"
##

@NODE PersonalEdit "Entering and Editing Personal Information"
               Entering and Editing Personal Information

When a new person is added to the database (by clicking the mouse on the
@{" Add New Person " LINK AddNewPerson} gadget) or when an existing database is opened, the
Personal Details Window displayed is where information about each person
may be edited or added.

To enter or edit information in a particular field, just click on that
field. For example, to enter the birth date just click on the Birth Date
field and then enter the date in the @{" date requester " LINK DateReq} that will appear.

Pressing RETURN or TAB in a text entry filed will automatically take you to
the next text entry field. Pressing Shift-TAB will take you to the
preceding text entry field.

See also @{" Dates " LINK DateField} and @{" Entry Shortcuts " LINK Shortcuts}.

To reduce the amount of typing required, and to help ensure that Last Names
are consistent, use the @{" Pick " LINK PickName} gadget located beside the Last Name entry
field. Select (from the list displayed) the Last Name that you want entered
into the Last Name field.

See also "Carry-over last names" under @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour}.

If a Last Name should not be fully capitalised (for example, MacDONALD is
preferred over MACDONALD) then these names should be added to the "Name
Exceptions" list. Then, for example, if the Last Name is entered as
"macdonald", it will be capitalised to "MacDONALD".

See @{" Set Name Exceptions " LINK Exceptions} under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu for more details.

See also @{" Setting Sex " LINK SetSex}.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Set Sex"
##

@NODE SetSex "Setting Sex"
                             Setting Sex

Clicking on this gadget will cycle through three sex choices - male,
female or unknown.

The small box underneath the gadget indicates the current sex. With the
default colour scheme, this is RED for females, BLUE for males and YELLOW
for unknown sex.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Dates"
##

@NODE DateField "Dates"
                               Dates
                               =====
Dates may range from 4000BC to 4000AD. The abbreviation "BC" will always
be used for "Before Christ" dates. That is, "BC" is NOT localised for
different languages in printed reports.

Dates may be "year only", "year and month", or "year, month and day" dates.
Note that "year and day" and "month and day" dates are illegal and
meaningless!

NOTE: There may be occasions when you know, for example, that "great-aunt
      Ann died on Christmas Day, but we don't know what year". Because
      "no-year" dates are not permitted in Scion, either estimate a year
      and mark the date as 'circa', or record the date in the 'comments'
      field.

Dates can contain "special" characters -

      < means that the date is a "before" date
      > means that the date is an "after" date
      ~ means that the date is a "circa" date
      ? means that the date is an "uncertain" date
      # means that the date is a "calculated" date

Examples of the displayed date format used:

	"Before" date: <23 March 1879 (meaning "Before 23 March 1879")
	"After" date:  >23 March 1879 (meaning "After 23 March 1879")
	"Circa" date:  ~23 March 1879 (meaning "Circa 23 March 1879")

Where an event date is marked as "uncertain" a question mark is appended to
the date. For example, "23 March 1879?"

Dates/ages/durations that have been calculated from the current (today's)
date will be preceded by a "#" character. For example, "#42".

Where an event date is marked as "BC" then "BC" is appended to the date.
For example, "1200BC".

Death dates may also be set to be "Dead" where a person is known to be
deceased, but the actual death date is unknown.

See also:
@{" Date Requesters " LINK DateReq}  @{" Death Date " LINK DeathDate}  @{" Ended Date " LINK EndedDate}  @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}  @{" Years Married " LINK YearsWed}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Death Date"
##

@NODE DeathDate "Death Date"
                              Death Date

The "Death Date" requester has an additional checkbox labelled
"Dead (No Date)". 

Where a person is known to be dead, but the date of death is not known,
check this gadget. This will set the person's death date to "Dead".

@{" Date Requesters " LINK DateReq}  @{" Ended Date " LINK EndedDate}  @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Ended Date"
##

@NODE EndedDate "Ended Date"
                              Ended Date

The "Ended Date" requester has an additional gadget labelled "Get First
Death".

Where the reason for the end of a marriage is the death of one of the
partners, then clicking on this button will copy the earlier death date of
the marriage partners into the date fields. This helps to keep dates within
the database correct.

For example, if the Principal has a death date of 2 Feb 1947 and
the Spouse has a death date of 23 Apr 1953, then clicking on the "Get First
Death" gadget will copy "2 Feb 1947" into the date fields.

Selecting the "Get First Death" gadget will also update the @{" End Reason " LINK EndReason}
gadget to show "Death", but ONLY if the date obtained is not further
modified while this requester is displayed.

@{" Date Requesters " LINK DateReq}  @{" Death Date " LINK DeathDate}  @{" Years Married " LINK YearsWed}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Entry Shortcuts"
##

@NODE Shortcuts "Entry Shortcuts"
                             Entry Shortcuts

To speed data entry, there are a number of key shortcuts available when
entering data into any data field.

<Esc>			Pressing the <Esc> key in any data entry field will
			cancel further entry into that field. No other
			field will be activated.

ALT CURSOR RIGHT	Will move the cursor to the next word

ALT CURSOR LEFT		Will move the cursor to the previous word

ALT BACKSPACE		Will delete the previous word (the one to the left
			of the cursor)

ALT DEL			Will delete the next word (the one to the right of
			the cursor)

ALT CURSOR UP		Will move the cursor to the previous data entry
			field

ALT CURSOR DOWN		Will move the cursor to the next data entry field

"	Entering a " character (single double-quote) as the first character
	in a data entry field will, when <enter> is pressed, copy the entry
	in the field above into the current data entry field.

	For example, entering " into the "Burial Place" field will cause
	the entry in the "Death Place" field to be copied into the "Burial
	Place" field.

=	Entering a = character (single equal-sign) as the first character
	in a data entry field will, when <enter> is pressed, copy the entry
	in the same field in the PREVIOUS record into the current data
	entry field.

	For example, entering = into the "Occupation" field will cause
	the entry in the "Occupation" field of the previous person to be
	copied into the "Occupation" field of the current person.

Data entry fields also support @{" clipboard copy and paste " LINK Copy&Paste}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Clipboard Copy and Paste"
##

@NODE Copy&Paste "Clipboard Copy and Paste"
                         Clipboard Copy and Paste

The data entry fields of Scion support the "copy" and "paste" functions of
the clipboard.

When the cursor is within any data entry field, the clipboard keys are:

Right-Amiga C - will copy the current contents of the field to the
                clipboard

Right-Amiga V - will paste the contents of the clipboard into the current
                data entry field

This facility uses the "standard" Amiga clipboard, so will allow
interchange of data with any other application supporting the clipboard.
For example, if a text editor supports the clipboard, you could then "copy"
the data from a particular Scion data entry field into the clipboard, and
then paste that data into a text document by using "paste" from within the
text editor. 
@ENDNODE

##
## "Pick Gadget"
##

@NODE PickName "Pick Gadget"
                             "Pick" Gadget
            (Located to the right of the Last Name entry field)

Every time that the <RETURN> or <TAB> key is pressed while in the Last Name
entry field, that last name is checked against a list of names maintained
in the "Last Name Pick List". If the current name is unique, it is added to
that pick list. This list maintains the 14 most recent unique last names
entered.

To transfer a last name from the pick list into the Last Name entry field,
simply click on the appropriate name in the list. That name will then be
transferred into the Last Name field where it may be accepted or edited.

This reduces the amount of typing required, and also ensures consistent
spelling of last names.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Navigating Around the Personal Database"
##

@NODE PersonalNavigation "Navigating Around the Personal Database"
               Navigating Around the Personal Database

The move around the Personal Database, use the "SELECT PERSON" gadgets:

     @{"  |<  " LINK FirstPerson} Select the first person (in IRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is shift-left-arrow
     @{"  <   " LINK PrevPerson} Select the previous person (in IRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is left-arrow
     @{" LIST " LINK ListPeople} Display selection list of the people in the database
              Key shortcut is '='
     @{"  #   " LINK WhatIRN} Go directly to a particular person's record when their IRN
            is known.
              Key shortcut is '#'
     @{"  >   " LINK NextPerson} Select the next person (in IRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is right-arrow
     @{"  >|  " LINK LastPerson} Select the last person (in IRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is shift-right-arrow

You can also step through the Personal Database using the alt-left-arrow
and alt-right-arrow keys. These keys will step through the database in
steps of approximately 10% of the database size. For example, if there are
60 people in the Personal Database, these keys will step by 6 people.

The IRN (Individual Record Number) of the currently displayed database
entry is displayed at the bottom centre of the window.

To search for (and go to the entry for) a particular person in the
database, the @{" Personal Search " LINK PersonSearch} gadget can be used.

To locate a particular ancestor, and go to the entry for a particular
ancestor, use the @{" Ancestors " LINK Ancestors} gadget.

To locate a particular descendant, and go to the entry for a particular
descendant, use the @{" Descendants " LINK DescList} gadget.

To locate a particular sibling, and go to the entry for a particular
sibling, use the @{" < Sibling " LINK PrevSibling} and @{" Sibling > " LINK NextSibling} gadgets.

To locate the current person's father, and go to his entry, use the
@{" Father " LINK GotoFather} gadget.

To locate the current person's mother, and go to her entry, use the
@{" Mother " LINK GotoMother} gadget.

To locate the current person's spouse, and go to their entry, use the
@{" Spouse " LINK GotoSpouse} gadget.

                                 --oo--

To move to Family Details Windows, use the "SELECT FAMILY" gadgets in the
right-hand "tool-bar" area:

     @{" Parents/Siblings " LINK Parents} Select the person's parent's Family Details Window
     @{" Spouse/Children  " LINK SpouseKids} Select the Family Details Window for the current
                        person's marriage
     @{" Family List      " LINK FamilyList} Select a family from a list of families
     @{" Go to Family     " LINK GotoFamily} Select a family using a known FGRN

You can also shift-click on the @{" Father " LINK GotoFather} or @{" Mother " LINK GotoMother} gadgets to go to the
Family Details Window for the current person's parents and siblings.

Similarly, you can shift-click on the @{" Spouse " LINK GotoSpouse} gadget to go to the Family
Details Window for the current person's (displayed) spouse and children.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Personal Details Window Gadgets"
##

@NODE PersonalGadgets "Personal Details Window Gadgets"
                        Personal Details Window Gadgets

  SELECT PERSON Gadgets (bottom right-hand side of window)
   @{"  |<  " LINK FirstPerson} @{"  <  " LINK PrevPerson} @{" LIST " LINK ListPeople} @{" # " LINK WhatIRN} @{"  >  " LINK NextPerson} @{"  >|  " LINK LastPerson}

  "TOOL-BAR" Gadgets (right-hand edge of window)
   @{" View/Edit Notes  " LINK PersonEditor}      @{" Add New Person   " LINK AddNewPerson}      @{" Parents/Siblings " LINK Parents}
   @{" View Picture     " LINK ViewPerson}      @{" Delete Person    " LINK DeletePerson}      @{" Spouse/Children  " LINK SpouseKids}
   @{" Play Sound File  " LINK PlaySound}      @{" Set 1st Marriage " LINK SetMarriage}      @{" Family List...   " LINK FamilyList}
                                                   @{" Go to Family...  " LINK GotoFamily}
                                                   @{" Personal Search  " LINK PersonSearch}

  SELECT OTHER Gadgets (bottom left-hand side of window)
   @{" Ancestors " LINK Ancestors} @{" Descendants " LINK DescList} @{" < Siblings " LINK PrevSibling} @{" Siblings > " LINK NextSibling}

  Miscellaneous Gadgets
   @{" Father " LINK GotoFather} @{" Mother " LINK GotoMother} @{" Spouse " LINK GotoSpouse} @{" Pick " LINK PickName} @{" ? # " LINK StatQuick}

  STATISTICS Area
   The data in this area is maintained automatically by the programme.

    Age       = age of current person. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
    Siblings  = total number of siblings of current person
    Marriages = total number of marriages for current person
    Children  = total number of offspring of current person (all marriages)

  See also @{" Statistics " LINK Statistics}.
@ENDNODE

##
## "First Person Gadget"
##

@NODE FirstPerson "First Person Gadget"
                       "|<" (First Person) Gadget

Clicking on the "|<" (First Person) gadget will take you to the window for
the first person in the database (in IRN numerical order).

If the "|<" (First Person) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
you are already at the first person in the database and the gadget will do
nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "shift-left-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Previous Person Gadget"
##

@NODE PrevPerson "Previous Person Gadget"
                     "<" (Previous Person) Gadget

Clicking on the "<" (Previous Person) gadget will take you to the window
for the preceding person (in IRN numerical order).

If the "<" (Previous Person) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means
that you are at the first person in the database and the gadget will do
nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "left-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "List People Gadget"
##

@NODE ListPeople "List People Gadget"
                            List People Gadget

Clicking on the "List People" gadget will display a list of every person
in the database.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

To display a particular person's Personal Details Window, simply click on
that person in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.

The number displayed at the bottom centre of the Personal Details Window is
the current IRN.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in people lists. In the "birth"
column, underlined dates represent BAPTISM dates (used in the absence of a
birth date), and in the "death" column, underlined dates represent BURIAL
dates (used in the absence of a death date).

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "=".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Next Person Gadget"
##

@NODE NextPerson "Next Person Gadget"
                        ">" (Next Person) Gadget

Clicking on the ">" (Next Person) gadget will take you to the window for
the next person (in IRN numerical order).

If the ">" (Next Person) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more people in the database and the gadget will do nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "right-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Last Person Gadget"
##

@NODE LastPerson "Last Person Gadget"
                       ">|" (Last Person) Gadget

Clicking on the ">|" (Last Person) gadget will take you to the window for
the last person in the database (in IRN numerical order).

If the ">|" (Last Person) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more people in the database and the gadget will do nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "shift-right-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Personal Note Viewer/Editor Gadget"
##

@NODE PersonEditor "Personal Note Viewer/Editor Gadget"
                            View/Edit Notes Gadget

Clicking on this gadget will VIEW a personal note. SHIFT-clicking on this
gadget will EDIT a personal note.

Clicking on the "View/Edit Notes" gadget will either display/edit an
attached note (an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately
to the right of the gadget), or raise a file requester where you can enter
the name of the free-form note that you wish to view/edit. The viewer or
editor that will be used is defined using the @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer} and
@{" Choose Notes Editor " LINK ChooseEditor} options under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu. If no Notes
Viewer is defined, the internal notes viewer will be used.

See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.

By default the notes are assigned the name PNx.database, where "PN" stands
for "Personal Notes", "x" is the IRN of the current person displayed, and
"database" is the name of the database. The name of the database is defined
when you save the database.

The default name can be ignored, and the notes file can be given any name.
(Note that the "pattern" field in the file requester may have to be
changed so that you can see files with other than the default names. Enter
#? as the pattern to see ALL files.)

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "1" for viewing, "!" for editing.
@ENDNODE

##
## "View Personal Picture Gadget"
##

@NODE ViewPerson "View Personal Picture Gadget"
                            View Picture Gadget

Clicking on the "ViewPicture" gadget will either display an attached
picture (an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately to the
right of the gadget), or raise a file requester where you can enter the
name of the IFF picture file that you wish to view. The viewer that will
used will either be Scion's in-built viewer or a user-defined viewer
defined using the @{" Choose Viewer " LINK ChooseViewer} option under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.

By default the pictures are assigned the name PPx.database, where "PP"
stands for "Personal Picture", "x" is the IRN of the current person
displayed, and "database" is the name of the database. The name of the
database is defined when you save the database.

The default name can be ignored, and the picture file can be given any
name.  (Note that the "pattern" field in the file requester may have to be
changed so that you can see files with other than the default names. Enter
#? as the pattern to see ALL files.)

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "2".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Play Sound File Gadget"
##

@NODE PlaySound "Play Sound File Gadget"
                         Play Sound File Gadget

Clicking on the "Play Sound File" gadget will either play an attached sound
file (an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately to the
right of the gadget), or raise a file requester where you can enter the
name of the sound file that you wish to play. The sound player that will be
used is either Scion's internal player, or an alternative one defined using
the @{" Choose Sound Player " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer} option under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.

By default the sound files are assigned the names PSx.database or
FSx.database, where "PS" stands for "Personal Sound" and "FS" stands for
"Family Sound", "x" is the IRN/FGRN of the current person/family displayed,
and "database" is the name of the database. The name of the database is
defined when you save the database.

The default name can be ignored, and the sound file can be given any
name.  (Note that the "pattern" field in the file requester may have to be
changed so that you can see files with other than the default names. Enter
#? as the pattern to see ALL files.)

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "3".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Personal Search Gadget"
##

@NODE PersonSearch "Personal Search Gadget"
                           Personal Search gadget

                          Keyboard shortcut is "+"

This gadget allows you to search for a particular individual in the
database.

After clicking on the "Personal Search" gadget you will be presented with a
requester asking for "Last Name", "First Names", "Place" and "Date Range".
Type the name of the person you are trying to find into the "name" fields.
To limit the search to a particular place of birth, baptism, death or
burial, enter a place-name into the "place" field. Note that Scion will
search all these event place fields to find a match for the "place"
entered.  To further limit the search to a date range, enter "start" and
"end" dates into the appropriate date fields. If no "start" date is
entered, Scion will search for any date up to any specified "end" date. If
no "end" date is entered, Scion will search for all dates later than any
specified "start" date. Therefore, if no "start" or "end" dates are
entered, Scion will ignore dates while searching.

Click on "Find First" to find (and display) the Personal Details Window for
the first person in the database matching your entries.

On first starting the programme, the Last Name and First Name(s) and Place
fields will contain ".*". This represents a @{" Regular Expression " LINK Regex} matching
ANY person and place in the database. In this (default) case, clicking on
"Find Next" will take you to the Personal Details Window for the next
person in IRN numerical order.

If the search fields already contain the name(s), etc that you want (from a
previous search) click on "Find Next" to move to the Personal Details
Window for the next person in the database matching your entries, or
click on "Find Prev" to move to the Personal Details Window for the
previous person in the database matching your entries.

When you have located the person of interest, clicking "Cancel" will remove
the search requester from display.

If the screen flashes when carrying out a search, that means that there are
no more matching entries in the database.

NOTE: You can search for event place names ONLY by entering the ".*"
      pattern into the personal name fields, and the place of interest into
      the "Place" field. Scion will then search for any record matching
      this place-name in the birth, baptism, death or burial place fields.

      Similarly, by entering ".*" into the Place field as well, and
      entering a "start" date and an "end" date, Scion will search for
      all records with a birth, baptism, death or burial date within that
      range.
@ENDNODE


##
## "Add New Person Gadget"
##

@NODE AddNewPerson "Add New Person Gadget"
                          Add New Person Gadget

To add a new person to the database, click on the "Add New Person" gadget.
After confirming that that is what you want to do, you will be presented
with a blank Personal Details Window (assigned the next available IRN) and
information about the new person can immediately be entered.

If the programme behaviour is set to "no confirmation" (using the
"Confirm 'Add Person'" option), the programme will not ask to confirm the
addition of the new person. See @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour}.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "4".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Delete Person Gadget"
##

@NODE DeletePerson "Delete Person Gadget"
                          Delete Person Gadget

To remove a person from the database, click on the "Delete Person" gadget.
You will be asked to confirm your actions before the record is actually
removed.  Not only will the person's Personal Details Window data be
deleted, but ALL references to that person as a child of a family or a
partner in a marriage will also be removed.  Any marriages that the person
was a partner in will be dissolved, and the person will no longer be a
parent of any of the children of that family group.

WARNING: Once you have removed a person from the database, their
         information is irretrievably lost, and their IRN and
         corresponding Personal Details Window are available for
	 reassignment.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "5".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Set 1st Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE SetMarriage "Set 1st Marriage"
                          Set 1st Marriage Gadget

If there are no marriages recorded for the current person, clicking on the
"Set 1st Marriage" gadget will, after confirmation, create a family group
corresponding to the first marriage of this person. A spouse and any
children may then be added to the resulting family group.

If the gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that the first marriage
has already been established for this person and the gadget will do
nothing. You can go to the Family Details Window for the (established)
first marriage by clicking on the @{" Spouse/Children " LINK SpouseKids} gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "6".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Parents/Siblings Gadget"
##

@NODE Parents "Parents/Siblings Gadget"
                        Parents/Siblings Gadget

Clicking on the "Parents/Siblings" gadget will take you to the Family
Details Window for the person's parents where the person's siblings
(brothers and sisters) are also displayed.

People have their parents established when a person is added to a family
group as a child.

NOTE: This gadget is annotated with "P" for (P)arents/Siblings to help
      distinguish between this gadget and the @{" Spouse/Children " LINK SpouseKids} gadget
      which has similar imagery. The "P" is NOT a keyboard shortcut.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "7".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Spouse/Children Gadget"
##

@NODE SpouseKids "Spouse/Children Gadget"
                        Spouse/Children Gadget

If a family group (marriage) is established for this person, clicking on
this gadget will take you to the first Family Details Window for that
person.

NOTE: This gadget is annotated with "S" for (S)pouse/Children to help
      distinguish between this gadget and the @{" Parents/Siblings " LINK Parents} gadget
      which has similar imagery. The "S" is NOT a keyboard shortcut.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "8".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Family List Gadget"
##

@NODE FamilyList "Family List Gadget"
                          Family List Gadget

Clicking on the "Family List" gadget will display a list of every family
in the database.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

To display a particular family's Family Details Window, simply click on
that family in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in family lists. In the "married"
column, underlined dates represent ENGAGEMENT dates (used in the absence of
a marriage date).

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "9".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Go to Family Gadget"
##

@NODE GotoFamily "Go to Family Gadget"
                        Go to Family Gadget

If the FGRN of a family of interest is known and you want to move directly
to their Family Details Window, click on this gadget and type in the FGRN
for that family. When  the <RETURN> key is pressed, the Family Details
Window for that family will be displayed.

To return to the Personal Details Window for the current person, select
the "Cancel" gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "0".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Father Gadget"
##

@NODE GotoFather "Father Gadget"
                           Father Gadget

Clicking on the "Father" gadget will move to the Personal Details Window
for the father of the currently displayed person.

Shift-clicking on "Father" gadget will take you to the Family Details
Window for the parents and siblings of the currently displayed person
(if defined).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Mother Gadget"
##

@NODE GotoMother "Mother Gadget"
                           Mother Gadget

Clicking on the "Mother" gadget will move to the Personal Details Window
for the mother of the currently displayed person.

Shift-clicking on "Mother" gadget will take you to the Family Details
Window for the parents and siblings of the currently displayed person
(if defined).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Spouse Gadget"
##

@NODE GotoSpouse "Spouse Gadget"
                           Spouse Gadget

Clicking on the "Spouse" gadget will move to the Personal Details Window
for the current spouse shown for the currently displayed person.

To select the current spouse when the person is married more than once,
click on the "<" or ">" arrows at the right-hand side of the spouse display
area.

Shift-clicking on "Spouse" gadget will take you to the Family Details
Window for the spouse and children of the currently displayed person
(if defined).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Previous Spouse Gadget"
##

@NODE PrevSpouse "Previous Spouse Gadget"
                           Previous Spouse Gadget

If the current displayed spouse is one of a number of spouses of the
displayed person, clicking on this button will select the preceding
spouse.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Next Spouse Gadget"
##

@NODE NextSpouse "Next Spouse Gadget"
                           Next Spouse Gadget

If the current displayed spouse is one of a number of spouses of the
displayed person, clicking on this button will select the following spouse.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Ancestors Gadget"
##

@NODE Ancestors "Ancestors Gadget"
                            Ancestors Gadget

Clicking on the "Ancestors" gadget will display an on-screen ancestor chart
for the current person. To move to the Personal Details Window for a
particular ancestor, click on their name in the ancestor chart. To return
to the Personal Details Window for the current person, select the "Cancel"
gadget.

Note that you can "promote" any person in the list to be the "base person"
by holding down the shift key and clicking on the person to "promote". For
example, if YOU are the "base person" in the list (the one at the extreme
left), then you can make your grandfather the new "base person" by holding
down the shift key and clicking on your grandfather's entry.

NOTE: Sex-less people will "break" ancestor lists. Hence nobody will appear
"above" sexless people.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is ">".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Descendants Gadget"
##

@NODE DescList "Descendants Gadget"
                          Descendants Gadget

Clicking on the "Descendants" gadget will display an on-screen descendant
chart for the current person. To move to the Personal Details Window for
a particular descendant, click on their name in the descendant chart. To
return to the Personal Details Window for the current person, select the
"Cancel" gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "<".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Go to Previous Sibling Gadget"
##

@NODE PrevSibling "Go to Previous Sibling Gadget"
                     Go to Previous Sibling Gadget

Clicking on the "Previous Sibling" gadget will move to the Personal
Details Window for the previous sibling of the currently displayed person.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "ctrl-left-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Go to Next Sibling Gadget"
##

@NODE NextSibling "Go to Next Sibling Gadget"
                      Go to Next Sibling Gadget

Clicking on the "Next Sibling" gadget will move to the Personal Details
Window for the next sibling of the currently displayed person.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "ctrl-right-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Select IRN Gadget"
##

@NODE WhatIRN "Select IRN Gadget"
                          "#" Select IRN Gadget

If the IRN of a person of interest is known and you want to move directly
to their Personal Details Window, click on this gadget and type in the IRN
for that person. When  the <RETURN> key is pressed, the Personal Details
Window for that person will be displayed.

To return to the Personal Details Window for the current person, select
the "Cancel" gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "#".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Statistics/Quick-help Gadget"
##

@NODE StatQuick "Statistics/Quick-help Gadget"
                      Statistics/Quick-help Gadget

Clicking on this gadget will alternate between displaying, in the bottom
line of the window, "quick-help" about window gadgets or @{" statistics " LINK Statistics}.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Statistics"
##

@NODE Statistics "Statistics"
                            Statistics Area

Personal Details Window:
   Age        = age of current person. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
   Siblings   = total number of siblings of current person
   Marriages  = total number of marriages for current person
   Children   = total number of offspring of current person (all marriages)

Family Details Window:
   Principal      = age of Principal at date of marriage. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
   Spouse         = age of Principal at date of marriage. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
   Years Married  = length of marriage of Principal and Spouse
                    See also @{" Years Married " LINK YearsWed}
   Children       = number of children in this family group
@ENDNODE

##
## "Ages"
##

@NODE AgeDisplay "Ages"
                               Ages

Ages are maintained automatically by Scion. The "rules" used to calculate
a person's age are as follows:

   If the birth date is accurate, and the death date is accurate, the age
      is the difference between the two dates
   If birth date is accurate, and death date is accurate, and age is less
      than 12 months, then age "<1"
   If the death date field contains the word "DEAD", then age is unknown
   If the age (for whatever reason) is greater than 125, then age is
      deemed to be unknown
   If birth date is absent, but baptism date is present, then age is
      calculated from the date of baptism and marked as uncertain by a
      trailing "?". If both birth and baptism fields are blank, then age
      is unknown.
   If death date is absent, but burial date is present, then age is
      calculated from the date of burial and marked as uncertain by a
      trailing "?"
   If both the death date and burial date are blank, then calculates the
      age from the difference between the birth (or baptism) date and the
      current (today's) date. Calculated age will be preceded by a "#" to
      indicate a "calculated" age

 Additionally:
    If any age is uncertain due to approximate dates or qualified dates
    (before/after/circa) then the age is appended with a "?"

 For principal's or spouse's age at marriage, the above rules also apply,
 but use the birth/baptism date and marriage/engagement date as the source
 dates for calculations.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Years Married"
##

@NODE YearsWed "Years Married"
                            Years Married

Years married are maintained automatically by Scion. The "rules" used to
calculate the duration of a marriage are as follows:

   If the wedding date is accurate, and the ending date is accurate, then
      the years married is the differnce between the two dates.
   If the wedding date and engagement date fields are blank, then years
      married is unknown.
   If wedding date is absent, but engagement date is present, then duration
      is calculated from the date of engagement and marked as uncertain by
      a trailing "?"
   If there is no ending date, then the duration is calculated from the
      wedding (or engagment) date, and the earlier death (or burial) date
      of either partner. For example, if the spouse died earlier than the
      principal, then the spouse's death (or burial) date will be used to
      calculate the marriage duration. In this case, the duration will be
      marked as uncertain (as indicated by a trailing "?").
   If the ending date field is blank AND neither partner has a specified
      death date, then the years married is the difference between the
      wedding date and the current (today's) date. The calculated years
      will be preceded by a "#" to indicate a "calculated" duration
   If the marriage duration (for whatever reason) is greater than 100, then
      duration is deemed to be unknown

 Additionally:
    If the duration is uncertain due to approximate dates or qualified
    dates (before/after/circa) then the duration is appended with a "?"
@ENDNODE

@REMARK Family Details Window Help *****************************************

##
## "Family Details Window"
##

@NODE FamilyWindow "Family Details Window"
                           FAMILY DETAILS WINDOW

The Family Group Window displays the Principal, Spouse and children making
up a family group and is where information about each family group may be
edited or added.

When you select "Spouse/Children" or "Parents/Siblings" from a Personal
Details Window, you will automatically change to the appropriate Family
Details Window.

You will also automatically change to the appropriate Family Details
Window when you create the first marriage for a person by selecting the
"Set 1st Marriage" gadget.

NOTE: Details on the various people making up the database should be
      entered FIRST and then the relationships between them can be
      established.

              @{" Entering and Editing Family Information " LINK FamilyEdit}
              @{" Navigating Around the Family Database   " LINK FamilyNavigation}
              @{" Family Details Window Gadgets           " LINK FamilyGadgets}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Entering and Editing Family Information"
##

@NODE FamilyEdit "Entering and Editing Family Information"
                 Entering and Editing Family Information

When a new family is added to the database or when an existing database is
opened, the Family Details Window is where information about each family
may be edited or added.

To enter or edit information in a particular field, just click on that
field. For example, to enter the engagement date just click on the
Engagement Date field and then enter the date in the @{" date requester " LINK DateReq} that
will appear.

Pressing RETURN or TAB in a text entry filed will automatically take you to
the next text entry field. Pressing Shift-TAB will take you to the
preceding text entry field.

See also @{" Dates " LINK DateField} and @{" Entry Shortcuts " LINK Shortcuts}.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Setting End Reason"
##

@NODE EndReason "Setting End Reason"
                         Setting End Reason

Clicking on this gadget will cycle through six choices for the ending of a
Family Group - unknown, none, divorce, separation, annulment or death.

This gadget is also set to "Death" if the @{" Ended Date " LINK EndedDate} is set using the
"Get First Death" option in the "Ended Date" requester.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Navigating Around the Family Database"
##

@NODE FamilyNavigation "Navigating Around the Family Database"
                   Navigating Around the Family Database

The move around the Family Database, use the "SELECT MARRIAGE" and
"SELECT FAMILY" gadgets:

 SELECT MARRIAGE Gadgets (bottom-left side of window):
     @{"  |<  " LINK FirstMarriage} Select the first marriage of the current Principal
     @{"  <   " LINK PrevMarriage} Select the previous marriage of the current Principal
     @{" LIST " LINK ListMarriages} Display selection list of the marriages of current Principal
     @{"  >   " LINK NextMarriage} Select the next marriage of the current Principal
     @{"  >|  " LINK LastMarriage} Select the last marriage of the current Principal

     @{" Exchange " LINK Exchange} Exchange Principal and Spouse. Key shortcut is 'X'.
                This gadget is located immediately to the right of the
		Principal and Spouse gadgets at the top of the window.

 SELECT FAMILY Gadgets (bottom-right side of window):
     @{"  |<  " LINK FirstFamily} Select the first family (in FGRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is shift-left-arrow
     @{"  <   " LINK PrevFamily} Select the previous family (in FGRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is left-arrow
     @{" LIST " LINK ListFamilies} Display selection list of the families in the database
              Key shortcut is '='
     @{"  #   " LINK WhatIRN} Go directly to a particular family's record when their FGRN
            is known.
              Key shortcut is '#'
     @{"  >   " LINK NextFamily} Select the next family (in FGRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is right-arrow
     @{"  >|  " LINK LastFamily} Select the last family (in FGRN numerical order)
              Key shortcut is shift-right-arrow

You can also step through the Family Database using the alt-left-arrow
and alt-right-arrow keys. These keys will step through the database in
steps of approximately 10% of the database size. For example, if there are
60 families in the Family Database, these keys will step by 6 families.

You can also move directly to the Family Details Windows of the parents of
the current Principal or Spouse by shift-clicking on the @{" Principal " LINK Principal} or
@{" Spouse " LINK Spouse} gadgets.

Similarly, you can go directly to the Family Details Window for the first
marriage (if any) of a child by shift-clicking on that child in the Child
List area, or by shift-clicking on the @{" Selected Child " LINK Child} gadget.

The FGRN (Family Group Record Number) of the currently displayed database
entry is displayed at the bottom centre of the window.

To search for (and go to the entry for) a particular family in the
database, the @{" Family Search " LINK FamilySearch} gadget can be used.

                                 --oo--

To move to Personal Details Windows, use the "Principal"and "Spouse"
gadgets, and the "People List" and "Go to Person" gadgets in the right-hand
"tool-bar" area:

     @{" Principal    " LINK Principal} Select the current Principal's Personal Details Window
     @{" Spouse       " LINK Spouse} Select the current Spouse's Personal Details Window

     @{" People List  " LINK PeopleList} Select a person from a list of people
                      Key shortcut is '9'
     @{" Go to Person " LINK GotoPerson} Select a person using a known IRN
                      Key shortcut is '0'

To move to the Personal Details Window for a particular child, you can
either double-click on the child in the Children List, or click on the
selected @{" child " LINK Child} (if any) in the gadget immediately below the Children
List.

NOTE: If a family group is dissolved using the @{" Dissolve Family " LINK DissolveFamily} gadget,
      you will be returned to the Personal Details Window for the current
      Principal.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Family Details Window Gadgets"
##

@NODE FamilyGadgets "Family Details Window Gadgets"
                          Family Details Window Gadgets

 SELECT FAMILY Gadgets (bottom right-hand side of window)
  @{"  |<  " LINK FirstFamily} @{"  <  " LINK PrevFamily} @{" LIST " LINK ListFamilies} @{" # " LINK WhatFGRN} @{"  >  " LINK NextFamily} @{"  >|  " LINK LastFamily}

 SELECT MARRIAGE Gadgets (bottom left-hand side of window)
  @{"  |<  " LINK FirstMarriage} @{"  <  " LINK PrevMarriage} @{" LIST " LINK ListMarriages} @{"  >  " LINK NextMarriage} @{"  >|  " LINK LastMarriage}

 "TOOL-BAR" Gadgets (right-hand edge of window)
  @{" View/Edit Notes  " LINK FamilyEditor}      @{" Set Spouse       " LINK AddSpouse}      @{" People List... " LINK PeopleList}
  @{" View Picture     " LINK ViewFamily}      @{" Add Child        " LINK AddChild}      @{" Go to Person.. " LINK GotoPerson} 
  @{" Play Sound File  " LINK PlaySound}      @{" Remove Child     " LINK RemoveChild}      @{" Family Search  " LINK FamilySearch}
                          @{" Dissolve Family  " LINK DissolveFamily}
                          @{" New Marriage     " LINK NewMarriage}

 SELECT PERSON Gadgets
  @{" Principal " LINK Principal} Select Principal (shift-click to display Principal's parents)
  @{" Spouse    " LINK Spouse} Select Spouse (shift-click to display Spouse's parents)
  @{" Child     " LINK Child} Select "selected" Child (shift-click to display child's
              first marriage)

 Miscellaneous Gadgets
  @{" Exchange " LINK Exchange} @{" ? # " LINK StatQuick}

 STATISTICS Area
  The data in this area is maintained automatically by the programme.

  Principal      = age of Principal at date of marriage. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
  Spouse         = age of Principal at date of marriage. See also @{" Ages " LINK AgeDisplay}
  Years Married  = length of marriage of Principal and Spouse
                   See also @{" Years Married " LINK YearsWed}
  Children       = number of children in this family group

 See also @{" Statistics " LINK Statistics}.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Select Principal Gadget"
##

@NODE Principal "Select Principal Gadget"
                          Select Principal Gadget

Clicking on the Principal's gadget will take you to the Personal Details
Window for the Principal of the currently displayed family group.

Shift-clicking on Principal's gadget will take you to the Family Details
Window for the parents of the Principal (if defined).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Select Spouse Gadget"
##

@NODE Spouse "Select Spouse Gadget"
                           Select Spouse Gadget

Clicking on the Spouse's gadget will take you to the Personal Details
Window for the Spouse of the currently displayed family group.

Shift-clicking on Spouse's gadget will take you to the Family Details
Window for the parents of the Spouse (if defined).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Selected Child Gadget"
##

@NODE Child "Selected Child Gadget"
                            Selected Child Gadget

Clicking on the "Selected Child" gadget immediately below the Children list
will take you to the Personal Details Window for the currently highlighted
child of the currently displayed family group.

To highlight a child, click on the child in the list immediately above the
"Selected Child" gadget.

You can also go directly to the Personal Details Window for a child by
double-clicking on the child of interest in the Children list.

Shift-clicking on the "Selected Child" gadget will take you to the Family
Details Window for the first marriage (if any) of the selected child.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Children List"
##

@NODE ChildList "Children List"
                              Children List

This area contains a list of all the children attached to this family
group sorted by date of birth. See also @{" Dates " LINK DateField}.

To highlight a child, click on the child in this list. The selected child
will then be displayed in the gadget immediately below this list. You can
then use the @{" Selected Child " LINK Child} gadget to take you to the Personal Details
Window for the selected child.

You can also go directly to the Personal Details Window for a child by
double-clicking on the child of interest in the Children list.

Shift-clicking on a child in the list will take you to the Family Details
Window for the first marriage (if any) of that child.

Clicking on the @{" Remove Child " LINK RemoveChild} gadget also allows you to remove the
selected child from the family group.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in child lists. In the "birth"
column, underlined dates represent BAPTISM dates (used in the absence of a
birth date).
@ENDNODE

##
## "Exchange Gadget"
##

@NODE Exchange "Exchange Gadget"
                            Exchange Gadget
          (Located to the right of the Principal & Spouse names)

Clicking on the Exchange gadget will exchange the Principal and Spouse
in the current Family Details window. By using this gadget, you can trace
the marriages of either partner in a family group.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "X".
@ENDNODE

##
## "People List Gadget"
##

@NODE PeopleList "People List Gadget"
			   People List Gadget

Clicking on the "People List" gadget will display a list of every person
in the database.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

To display a particular person's Personal Details Window, simply click on
that person in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in people lists. In the "birth"
column, underlined dates represent BAPTISM dates (used in the absence of a
birth date), and in the "death" column, underlined dates represent BURIAL
dates (used in the absence of a death date).

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "9".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Go to Person Gadget"
##

@NODE GotoPerson "Go to Person Gadget"
                        Go to Person Gadget

If the IRN of a person of interest is known and you want to move directly
to their Personal Details Window, click on this gadget and type in the IRN
for that person. When  the <RETURN> key is pressed, the Personal Details
Window for that person will be displayed.

To return to the Family Details Window for the current family, select
the "Cancel" gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "0".
@ENDNODE

##
## "First Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE FirstMarriage "First Marriage Gadget"
                       "|<" (First Marriage) Gadget

Clicking on the "|<" (First Marriage) gadget will take you to the window
for the first marriage in the database for the current Principal.

If the "|<" (First Marriage) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means
that you are already at the first marriage for the current Principal and
the gadget will do nothing.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Previous Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE PrevMarriage "Previous Marriage Gadget"
                     "<" (Previous Marriage) Gadget

Clicking on the "<" (Previous Marriage) gadget will take you to the window
for the preceding Marriage of the current Principal.

If the "<" (Previous Marriage) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means
that you are at the first marriage for the current Principal and the gadget
will do nothing.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Marriages List Gadget"
##

@NODE ListMarriages "Marriages List Gadget"
                          Marriages List Gadget

Clicking on the "Marriages List" gadget will display a list of the spouses
of every marriage in the database for the current Principal.

If you are using a colour monitor, male spouses will be displayed in blue
and female spouses will be displayed in red. If a spouse's sex has not been
defined, their entry in the list will be displayed in yellow.

To display a particular marriage's Family Details Window, simply click on
that marriage in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Next Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE NextMarriage "Next Marriage Gadget"
                        ">" (Next Marriage) Gadget

Clicking on the ">" (Next Marriage) gadget will take you to the window
for the next marriage of the current Principal.

If the ">" (Next Marriage) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more marriages for the current Principal and the gadget will
do nothing.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Last Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE LastMarriage "Last Marriage Gadget"
                       ">|" (Last Marriage) Gadget

Clicking on the ">|" (Last Marriage) gadget will take you to the window for
the last marriage in the database for the current Principal.

If the ">|" (Last Marriage) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more marriages for the current Principal and the gadget will
do nothing.
@ENDNODE


##
## "First Family Gadget"
##

@NODE FirstFamily "First Family Gadget"
                       "|<" (First Family) Gadget

Clicking on the "|<" (First Family) gadget will take you to the window for
the first family in the database (in FGRN numerical order).

If the "|<" (First Family) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
you are already at the first family in the database and the gadget will do
nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "shift-left-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Previous Family Gadget"
##

@NODE PrevFamily "Previous Family Gadget"
                     "<" (Previous Family) Gadget

Clicking on the "<" (Previous Family) gadget will take you to the window
for the preceding family (in FGRN numerical order).

If the "<" (Previous Family) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means
that you are at the first family in the database and the gadget will do
nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "left-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Select FGRN Gadget"
##

@NODE WhatFGRN "Select FGRN Gadget"
                         "#" Select FGRN Gadget

If the FGRN of a family of interest is known and you want to move directly
to their Family Details Window, click on this gadget and type in the FGRN
for that family. When  the <RETURN> key is pressed, the Family Details
Window for that family will be displayed.

To return to the Family Details Window for the current family, select
the "Cancel" gadget.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "#".
@ENDNODE

##
## "List Families Gadget"
##

@NODE ListFamilies "List Families Gadget"
			    List Families Gadget

Clicking on the "Family List" gadget will display a list of every family
in the database.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

To display a particular family's Family Details Window, simply click on
that family in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.

The number displayed at the bottom centre of the Family Details Window is
the current FGRN.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in family lists. In the "married"
column, underlined dates represent ENGAGEMENT dates (used in the absence of
a marriage date).

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "=".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Next Family Gadget"
##

@NODE NextFamily "Next Family Gadget"
                        ">" (Next Family) Gadget

Clicking on the ">" (Next Family) gadget will take you to the window for
the next family (in FGRN numerical order).

If the ">" (Next Family) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more families in the database and the gadget will do nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "right-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Last Family Gadget"
##

@NODE LastFamily "Last Family Gadget"
                       ">|" (Last Family) Gadget

Clicking on the ">|" (Last Family) gadget will take you to the window for
the last family in the database (in IRN numerical order).

If the ">|" (Last Family) gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey) it means that
there are no more families in the database and the gadget will do nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "shift-right-arrow".
@ENDNODE

##
## "People Selection Lists" - Displayed as help on all types
##                            of people selection lists
##

@NODE PersSelectList "Person Selection Lists"
			    Person Selection Lists

These lists allow you to choose one and, in some cases, more than one
person.

Personal Selection Lists can be "filtered" to show a reduced list of
the people in the database. The number of people currently being displayed
in the list is displayed in the gadget immediately above the "filter"
gadget.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

In single-selection lists (which do NOT have an "Accept" button in the
bottom right-hand corner of the list window), clicking on one of the
people in the list selects that person.

In multi-selection lists (which DO have an "Accept" button in the
bottom right-hand corner of the list window), clicking on a person in
the list will select them (or deselect them if they are already
highlighted). When the appropriate number of people have been marked
as selected, pressing the "Accept" button accepts the current selections.

Multi-selection lists also have an attached menu. There are two items
in this menu -
       
       - Select all displayed
		Marks as "selected" all the people currently displayed
		in the list
       
       - Clear all selected
		"Deselects" everybody in the list already marked as
		selected

The "Select all displayed" item is very useful for generating reports.
For example, to print all the Personal Summaries for people with the
last name of "SMITH", use the "Selected..." option under the
"Personal Summary" print menu and use the filtering gadget at the bottom
of the resultant list window to show only those people with the last
name "SMITH". Then use the "Select all displayed" menu item to select
every "SMITH". Pressing the "Accept" button will then print the Personal
Summary for every "SMITH" in the database.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in people lists. In the "birth"
column, underlined dates represent BAPTISM dates (used in the absence of a
birth date), and in the "death" column, underlined dates represent BURIAL
dates (used in the absence of a death date).

@ENDNODE

##
## "Family Selection Lists" - Displayed as help on all types
##                            of family selection lists
##

@NODE FamSelectList "Family Selection Lists"
			    Family Selection Lists

These lists allow you to choose one and, in some cases, more than one
family.

Family Selection Lists can be "filtered" to show a reduced list of
the families in the database. The number of families currently being
displayed in the list is displayed in the gadget immediately above the
"filter" gadget.

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

In single-selection lists (which do NOT have an "Accept" button in the
bottom right-hand corner of the list window), clicking on one of the
families in the list selects that family.

In multi-selection lists (which DO have an "Accept" button in the
bottom right-hand corner of the list window), clicking on a family in
the list will select it (or deselect it if it is already highlighted). 
When the appropriate number of families have been marked as selected,
pressing the "Accept" button accepts the current selections.

Multi-selection lists also have an attached menu. There are two items
in this menu -
       
       - Select all displayed
		Marks as "selected" all the families currently displayed
		in the list
       
       - Clear all selected
		"Deselects" every family in the list already marked as
		selected

The "Select all displayed" item is very useful for generating reports.
For example, to print all the Family Group Sheets for families that have a 
marriage partner with the last name of "SMITH", use the "Selected..."
option under the "Family Group Sheet" print menu and use the filtering
gadget at the bottom of the resultant list window to show only those
families which have a partner with the last name "SMITH". Then use the
"Select all displayed" menu item to select every "SMITH" family. Pressing
the "Accept" button will then print the Family Group Sheets for every
"SMITH" family in the database.

NOTE: Some dates will appear under-lined in family lists. In the "married"
column, underlined dates represent ENGAGEMENT dates (used in the absence of
a marriage date).

@ENDNODE

##
## "Marriage Selection Lists" - Displayed as help on marriage selection lists
##

@NODE MarrySelectList "Marriage Selection Lists"
			    Marriage Selection Lists

Marriage Selection Lists display a list of the spouses of every marriage
in the database for the current Principal.

To display a particular marriage's Family Details Window, simply click on
that marriage in the list.  Selecting "Cancel" will return you to the
original window.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Ancestor Selection List" - Displayed as help on ancestor selection list
##

@NODE AncSelectList "Ancestor Selection List"
			    Ancestor Selection List

Ancestor Selection Lists display an on-screen ancestor chart for the
current person. To move to the Personal Details Window for a particular
ancestor, click on their name in the ancestor chart. To return to the
Personal Details Window for the current person, select the "Cancel" gadget.

Note that you can "promote" any person in the list to be the "base person"
by holding down the shift key and clicking on the person to "promote". For
example, if YOU are the "base person" in the list (the one at the extreme
left), then you can make your grandfather the new "base person" by holding
down the shift key and clicking on your grandfather's entry.

NOTE: Sex-less people will "break" ancestor lists. Hence nobody will appear
"above" sexless people.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Descendant Selection List" - Displayed as help on descendant selection list
##

@NODE DescSelectList "Descendant Selection List"
			    Descendant Selection List

Descendant Selection Lists display an on-screen descendant
chart for the current person. To move to the Personal Details Window for
a particular descendant, click on their name in the descendant chart. To
return to the Personal Details Window for the current person, select the
"Cancel" gadget.

Lists are restricted to the number of decendants that can be reasonably
displayed with the current screen mode and font (up to a maximum of
32 generations). If there are more generations than can reasonably fit
across the window, the additional descendants (not displayed) are indicated
by ">>>".

@ENDNODE

##
## "Number Requesters" - Displayed as help on all types
##                       of record number requesters
##

@NODE NumReq "Record Number Requester"
			    Record Number Requester

To move to a personal or family record where the IRN or FGRN is known,
enter the IRN or FGRN into the number gadget and press <Enter>.

Press <Esc> or click "Cancel" button to cancel.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Search Requesters" - Displayed as help on search requesters
##

@NODE SearchReq "Search Requester"
			    Search Requester

This requester allows you to search for people/families in the database.

Type the name of the person/marriage-partner you are trying to find into
the "name" fields.  To limit the search to a particular event place (such
as birth or wedding), enter a place-name into the "place" field. Note that
Scion will search ALL appropriate event place fields to find a match for
the "place" entered.  To further limit the search to a date range, enter
"start" and "end" dates into the appropriate date fields. If no "start"
date is entered, Scion will search for any date up to any specified "end"
date. If no "end" date is entered, Scion will search for all dates later
than any specified "start" date. Therefore, if no "start" or "end" dates
are entered, Scion will ignore dates while searching.

Click on "Find First" to find (and display) the record for the first
person/family in the database matching your entries.

On first starting the programme, the Last Name and First Name(s) and Place
fields will contain ".*". This represents a @{" Regular Expression " LINK Regex} matching
ANY person/family and place in the database. In this (default) case,
clicking on "Find Next" will take you to the record for the next
person/family in IRN/FGRN numerical order.

If the search fields already contain the name(s), etc that you want (from a
previous search) click on "Find Next" to move to the next record in the
database matching your entries, or click on "Find Prev" to move to the
previous record in the database matching your entries.

When you have located the record of interest, clicking "Cancel" will remove
the search requester from display.

If the screen flashes when carrying out a search, that means that there are
no more matching entries in the database.

NOTE: You can search for event place names ONLY by entering the ".*"
      pattern into the name fields, and the place of interest into
      the "Place" field. For personal searches, Scion will then search for
      any record matching this place-name in the birth, baptism, death or
      burial place fields. For family searches, Scion will search for
      any record matching this place-name in the engagement, wedding or
      ended place fields.

      Similarly, by entering ".*" into the Place field as well, and
      entering a "start" date and an "end" date, Scion will search for
      all records with a birth, baptism, death or burial date within that
      range for personal searches, and for family searches Scion will
      search for all records with an engagement, wedding or ended date
      within that range.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Name Exception Requester" - Displayed as help on name exception requesters
##

@NODE ExceptReq "Name Exception Requester"
			    Name Exception Requester

This requester allows you to maintain a list of Last Names that should not
be fully capitalised. For example, MacDONALD may be preferred over
MACDONALD.  Scion will automatically choose the correct capitalisation of a
Last Name from this list.

To add a new name to the list, type the name as you wish it to be
capitalised (for example, MacDONALD) into the entry field near the bottom
of the list and then press <enter>. The name will now be displayed in the
list above.

To change an existing entry in the list, click on the name in the main list
area. The name will now be displayed in the entry field near the bottom of
the list. Type the corrections required, and then press <enter>. The
changed name will be added back to the main list.

To delete an entry in the list, click on the name in the main list area.
The name will now be displayed in the entry field near the bottom of the
list. Click on the "Delete" button. The name has now been removed from the
list.

When you are satisfied with the contents of the Name Exception list, click
on the "Accept" button.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Address Requester" - Displayed as help on all types of (name)/address requesters
##

@NODE AddressReq "Address Requester"
			    Address Requester

This requester allows you to enter the address and telephone number of a
person or a family. It is also used to enter the NAME, address and
telephone number of the person preparing the database.

If the number of lines displayed does not provide enough fields, each line
can contain more than a single item. For example, the first line could
contain something like - "Ettrick Cottage, 42 High Street".  Each
"component" entered on a single line should be separated by a comma. Do NOT
add a comma at the end of each line - Scion will append this automatically.

Similarly, if you wish to record a FAX number or an email address, add
these to the "telephone" line as in the following example -

    "+64 +4 555-9876, FAX: 555-1234, email: jdoe@provider.net"

In this example, "+64 +4 555-9876" is the telephone number. The FAX and
email details are appended to this.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Function Key Requester" - Displayed as help on function key requesters
##

@NODE FunKeyReq "Function Key Requester"
			    Function Key Requester

This requester allows you to define operations that can be carried out
using the Amiga function keys F1...F10, and the shift/alt/ctrl'd function
keys, for a total of 40 different function key assignments.

Typically these keys could be used to issue ARexx commands, although any
valid command can be attached to a function key.

Type in the commands you want executed into the appropriate string
gadget(s) for the required function key(s) and then click on the "Accept"
button. To cancel out of the operation, click the "Cancel" button.

Example:
=======

Entering "rx REXX:Scion2GEDCOM" into the "F1" entry gadget will mean that
the Arexx programme "Scion2GEDCOM.rexx" will be run any time the F1
function key is pressed.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Behaviour Requester" - Displayed as help on behaviour requesters
##

@NODE BehaveReq "Programme Behaviour Requester"
                            Programme Behaviour Requester

This requester allows you to change the behaviour of Scion.
Refer to @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour} for more information.
@ENDNODE

##
## Sorting
##

@NODE Sorting "List Sorting"
                              List Sorting

People and family lists may be sorted in a number of different orders:

People Lists:     Alphabetical order
                  Numerical (IRN) order
                  Birth Date order
                  Death Date order

Family Lists:     Numerical (FGRN) order
                  Male's name order
                  Female's name order
                  Wedding Date order

By default, Scion uses a standard "cycle" type gadget in the bottom
left-hand corner of the displayed lists. Clicking on this cycle gadget will
step forwards through the sort choices, and shift-clicking will step
backwards through the choices.

Because Scion has to re-sort the list for every new choice, it means that
on some slower Amigas, or with large databases, that it can take some
seconds to cycle between choices (while the re-sorting is carried out).

To reduce this delay, you can optionally change the "cycle" gadget into a
"pop-up" type gadget. This gadget, when clicked, will show you a selection
of the sort options available. Move the mouse cursor over the sort-order of
choice and release the mouse button. Scion will then move directly to the
new sort-order without stepping through intermediate choices.

See also @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour}.
@ENDNODE

##
## Filtering and pattern matching
##

@NODE Filtering "Filtering and Pattern Matching"
                         Filtering and Pattern Matching

The selection lists displayed by Scion can be filtered using four different
methods -

	1. Show all names
	2. Last name matches
	3. Last name similar to
	4. Last name sounds like

The fields of the "Search" requesters ALWAYS use @{" regular expression " LINK Regex}
matching.

1. Show all names
   ==============
	This option performs NO filtering, and all possible entries are
	displayed in the list.

2. Last name matches
   =================
	This option performs "regular expression" filtering and is the most
	powerful option available for selectively displaying entries in
	the list. See @{" regular expressions " LINK Regex} for more details on this
	option.

        A SMALL TIP: When there are a number of "empty" people in a list
	(you might have just "bulk added" some), then these "empty"
	records can be excluded from the list by entering a pattern
	"[^$ ]". What this says is "anything NOT beginning with a space".

3. Last name similar to
   ====================
	This option filters the list to display names with similar
	SPELLINGS. The method used is the @{" Guth algorithm " LINK Guth}.

	This method will always find the exact match for a name, but will
	also return a significant number of apparently bizarre matches.
	This isn't a bug - it's just the way the algorithm works. This
	method works better on long names than short names.

4. Last name sounds like
   =====================
	This option filters the list to display names that SOUND similar.
	The method used is @{" Metaphone " LINK Metaphone} matching.

	This filtering method is an enhanced type of "soundex" algorithm.
	It is much more "robust" than the standard "Russell Soundex".
	However, because of this "robustness", it returns less matches than
	you might expect because of it's much tighter pronunciation rules.
	It will always return an exact match for the name.

NOTE: In options 2, 3 and 4, an "empty" name pattern will default to
      showing ALL entries in the database.

The number of matching entries currently being displayed in the list is
displayed in the gadget immediately above the "filter" gadget.
@ENDNODE

##
## Regular Expressions
##

@NODE Regex "Regular Expressions"
                            Regular Expressions

"Regular Expression" matching and filtering in Scion is extremely powerful.
It can be used to perform simple as well as very complex "filtering". While
complex patterns are difficult to explain in simple terms, it is worthwhile
attempting an understanding so that the full power available can be used.

"Regular Expression" filtering is the method used in lists to perform
"Last name matches" filtering. It is also the "matching" method used in
all "Search" requesters to match names and places.

See @{" Regular Expression Examples " LINK RegexExamples} for examples of using the power of this
matching and filtering method.

SPECIAL NOTE: Regular expression matching and filtering in Scion is NOT
case-sensitive.

Regular expressions have a syntax in which a few characters are 'special'
and the rest are "ordinary".  An ordinary character matches that character
and nothing else.  The special characters are `$', `^', `.', `*', `+', `?',
`[', `]' and `\'.  Any other character appearing in a regular expression is
ordinary, unless a `\' precedes it.

The following are the characters and character sequences which have special
meaning within regular expressions.  Any character not mentioned here is
not special; it stands for exactly itself for the purposes of searching and
matching.


`.'
     is a special "wildcard" character that matches ANY single character.
     Therefore, `a.b' will match any name which contains a three-character
     sequence that begins with `a' and ends with `b'. For example, 't.e'
     will match 'tie' and 'toe', but will not match 'te'.

`*'
     means that the preceding pattern is to be repeated as many times as
     possible.  In `to*', the `*' applies to the `o', so `to*' matches `t'
     followed by any number of `o''s (including none). Hence 'to*' will
     match 't', 'to', 'too', etc.

`+'
     `+' is like `*' except that AT LEAST ONE match for the preceding
     pattern is required for `+'.  Thus, `to+' does NOT match 't',
     but does match 'to', 'too', etc.

`?'
     `?' is like `*' except that it allows either ZERO OR ONE match
     for the preceding pattern.  Thus, `ti?e' matches `te' or `tie', and
     nothing else.

`[ ... ]'
     `[' begins a "character set", which ends with a `]'.  In the simplest
     case, the characters between the two form the "set".  Thus, `[ad]'
     matches either `a' or `d', and `[ad]*' matches any name with `a''s
     and `d''s (including the "null" name), from which it follows that
     `c[ad]*r' matches `car', etc.

     Character ranges can also be included in a character set, by
     writing two characters with a `-' between them.  Thus, `[a-z]'
     matches any lower-case letter. (SPECIAL NOTE: Regular expression
     matching and filtering in Scion is NOT case-sensitive.) Ranges may
     be intermixed freely with individual characters, as in `[a-z$%.]',
     which matches any lower case letter or `$', `%' or period.

     Note that the usual special characters are not special any more
     inside a character set.  A completely different set of special
     characters exists inside character sets: `]', `-' and `^'.

     To include a `]' in a character set, you must make it the first
     character.  For example, `[]a]' matches `]' or `a'.  To include
     a `-', it must be the first character, or immediately after a range.

`[^ ... ]'
     `[^' begins a "complement character set", which matches any
     character EXCEPT the ones specified.  Thus, `[^a-z0-9A-Z]'
     matches all characters *except* letters and digits.

     `^' is not special in a character set unless it is the first
     character.  The character following the `^' is treated as if it
     were first (it may be a `-' or a `]').

`^'
     is a special character that matches at the beginning of a name.
     Otherwise it fails to match anything.  Thus, `^tom' matches a
     `tom' which occurs at the beginning of a name. This does NOT (in
     general) apply with Scion "Search" requesters.

`$'
     is similar to `^' but matches only at the end of a name.  Thus,
     `ee*$' matches a name of one or more `e''s at the end of a name.
     This does NOT (in general) apply with Scion "Search" requesters.

`\'
     quotes the above special characters (including `\').

     Because `\' quotes special characters, `\$' is a pattern which
     matches only `$', and `\[' is a pattern which matches only `[',
     and so on.

`|'
     specifies an alternative.  Two patterns A and B with `|' in between
     form a pattern that matches anything that either A or B will match.

     Thus, `smith|jones' matches either `smith' or `jones' but no other
     name.

     `|' applies to the largest possible surrounding patterns. Only a
     surrounding `( ... )' grouping can limit the grouping power of `|'.

`( ... )'
     allows grouping that serves two purposes:

       1. To enclose a set of `|' alternatives for other operations.
          Thus, `(tin|phon)y' matches either `tiny' or `phony'.

       2. To enclose a complicated pattern for `*' to operate on. Thus,
          `ba(na)*' matches `bananana', etc., with any (zero or more)
	  number of `na''s.

See @{" Regular Expression Examples " LINK RegexExamples} for examples of using the power of this
matching and filtering method.
@ENDNODE

##
## Regular Expressions Examples
##

@NODE RegexExamples "Regular Expression Examples"
                        Regular Expression Examples

SPECIAL NOTE: Regular expression matching and filtering in Scion is NOT
case-sensitive.

(1) Simple pattern - 'ab' will match any name that contains the characters
    'ab' immediately adjacent to each other. Thus, 'ab' will match 'cAB',
    'fAB', 'ABout', 'cABinet', etc.

(2) "Wildcard" patterns - 't.e' will match any name containing 'TiE',
    'ToE', 'TaE', etc, but NOT 'te'.

(2) Character "sets" - 't[ao]m' will match 'TAM', 'TOM', aTOMic', sTAMp',
    etc. 

(3) Character "ranges" - 'f[a-e]x' will match any name that contains 'fAx',
    ''fBx', 'fCx', 'fDx', and 'fEx', but NOT 'fOx'.

(4) "Anchoured" pattern - '^tom' will match any name that STARTS with
    'tom'. Hence, '^tom' will match 'TOMpson', but will NOT match 'aTOM'.

    Similarly, 'th$' will match any name that ENDS with 'th'. Hence, 'th$'
    will match 'smiTH', 'wiTH', but will NOT match 'THick' or 'wiTHer'.

    This type of pattern can be used to "isolate" particular names in a
    list. For example, to show only people with the last name 'smith',
    but EXCLUDE such names as 'smithson' and 'blacksmith', use a pattern
    '^smith$'. What this means is that the name must begin AND end with
    the 'smith', hence excludes 'smithson' and 'blacksmith'. One note of
    caution, however - make sure that the names entered into the database
    do not have leading or trailing spaces (eg 'smith '). This will NOT
    match '^smith$' because it does not end with 'smith' - it ends with
    a space character.

    NOTE: These "anchoured" matches will NOT work in Search requesters.

(5) Alternative patterns - 'smith|jones' will match any names containing
    either 'smith' OR 'jones', but no others. Similarly, 'sm(i|y)th' will
    match 'SMITH' OR 'SMYTHe' OR 'goldSMITH'.

A SMALL TIP: When there are a number of "empty" people in a list (you
    might have just "bulk added" some), then these "empty" records can be
    excluded from the list by entering a pattern "[^$ ]". What this says
    is "anything NOT beginning with a space".

See also @{" Regular Expressions " LINK Regex} for details of this matching and filtering
method.
@ENDNODE


##
## Guth Algorithm
##

@NODE Guth "Guth Algorithm"
                             Guth Algorithm

      An Algorithm for Recognising Alternate Spellings of Surnames

This is a detailed description of the Guth Algorithm and is supplied for
interest only. It is not necessary to understand these details to be able
to use this filtering option in Scion.

===========================================================================
An extract from "Surname Spellings and Computerised Record Linkage" by
Gloria J.A.Guth. Historical Methods Newsletter, Vol.10, No.1, Dec.1976.
===========================================================================

Unfortunately, the spelling of the surnames varies quite a bit.
For example, the clerk of the Norwich poll in 1710 recorded "Peter
Bokenham" while the clerk in 1715 spelled the same surname "Buckingham."
A name recognition algorithm was devised to bring within reasonable
bounds the degree to which mismatches in surnames would still result in
record linkage. As with any general rule, it did not select some of the
most extreme variations in spellings, but it was able to identify and
link names such as "Smears" and "Smares" and "Gittins" and "Giddings."

Figure 1 (not included here) summarises the nine rules or tests used for
matching the letters of two surnames; note that they all depended on the
position of the letters in the names, their sequence or order, rather than
on what the letters themselves were. Thus there was no need to specify
phonetic rules of any sort.

The "most preferred" pattern was an exact correspondence between every
letter of each of the two names under scrutiny. Therefore, the first
step in the algorithm (not shown in Figure 1) was a check for identical
names, looking at each of the surnames as a single character string.

Failing that, the algorithm entered the loop shown in Figure 1 and
compared the two surnames letter by letter, considering each in turn. As
long as the two names were identical, the algorithm succeeded with Test
I and did not drop down through the rest of the loop. When a mismatch
occurred in the letter-for-letter comparison, the remaining eight tests
were tried in the order shown in Figure 1. A success with any of the
tests caused the algorithm to return to the beginning of the loop,
increment the counter by 1, check for the end of the name, and proceed
to go through the loop again comparing the next letters in the two names.
A search that failed to discover any of these patterns in the surnames
caused the linkage process to fail and the records to be rejected; a
successful matching of the surnames resulted in the two records being
passed to the rest of the linkage program for further tests of criteria
for linking.

                   Figure 1
Tests for Position of Letters in Matching Alternate Surname Spellings

      Position in Name 1   Position in Name 2
Test 1      X                   X
Test 2      X                   X+l
Test 3      X                   X+2
Test 4      X                   X-l
Test S      X-l                 X
Test 6      X+l                 X
Test 7      X+2                 X
Test 8      X+l                 X+l
Test 9      X+2                 X+2

As an example of this algorithm, consider the variation "Glawyn"
for the name "Glavin". In attempting to match these two surnames, the
algorithm succeeded in matching the first three letters without a problem.

The mismatch between the fourth letters of the two names, however, caused
the algorithm to try patterns other than the letter-for-letter matching
that initially was successful. First, a letter was skipped in the second
name and compared with the original letter in the first name, "y" and "v"
respectively. Next the algorithm skipped an additional letter in the
second name and compared the "v" with the "n" in the second name. The
fourth alternative caused the algorithm to compare the "v" with the "a"
in the second name, that is, the letter in position "x" in the first name
was compared with the letter in position "x-1" in the second name. Failing
that, the pointer remained stationary in the second name, and the algorithm
attempted matches with the letters in positions "x + 1, " and "x +2" in
the first name. Thus, the "w" in the second name was compared with the
letters "a," "i," and "n" respectively. These seven alternatives having
failed to produce a match of any sort, the algorithm tried the last two
alternatives. It skipped one letter in each name, resulting in a comparison
of the fifth letters, the "i" and the "y". The last alternative in fact
succeeded: the letters in position "x+2" in each name (in this case, the
sixth letters) were identical. The algorithm then incremented the position
pointer by one and began the loop again. However, preceding the attempt to
match the next two letters (the "i" in the first name and the "y" in the
second), the test for the end of the name overrode the matching process,
and the two records were considered similar enough to be linked. They were
then passed to the remainder of the linkage program to determine if they
met the other criteria required for linking on that run. The test for the
end of the name was quite simple; before every potential match of
letters, the algorithm determined whether the position of the two
letters, after the letter under consideration in either name (x+2), was
occupied by a blank. If so the names were considered matched, and the
examination of the two surnames was abandoned. Note that the test for
the end of the name did not succeed until after the two "n's" had been
matched because the letters then in question were the fourth ones, and
the test for the end of the name was made on that basis. That is, the
letter "x+2" in each name was at that point the sixth letter, which was
not a blank.

This algorithm had four principal advantages over other methods of
surname recognition. First, it was not dependent on the prior generation
of a sorting key, such as the Russell Soundex code, based on the
phonetics of the surname. Soundex, the most widely-used of such derived
codes, has proved not to be discriminating enough to deal with data
containing early modern variations in spelling. In other words, Soundex
generated sorting pockets that were too general for the Norwich data.
The second major advantage of this algorithm was that, like Soundex, it
was data-independent and could be adapted easily to different types of
data or linkage requirements. Thirdly, the name recognition algorithm
was designed to be incorporated into the actual record-linkage
procedures, permitting the degree of match in the surnames to be
included as one of criteria for record linkage, but it did not alter the
input records in any way. The fourth primary advantage was that
alternative spellings of the same name were identified by the position
of the letters in the surname and not by phonetic equivalency. The names
were linked on the basis of the order or sequence of the letters, and this
eliminated the problems either of trying to adapt Soundex's one alpha,
three numeric code to the given data or of developing one's own rules of
phonics, such as programming "ph" and "f" to be equivalent.
@ENDNODE

##
## Metaphone
##

@NODE Metaphone "Metaphone Matching"
                          Metaphone Matching

           A more accurate phonetic search (A Modern Soundex)

This is a detailed description of the Metaphone Algorithm and is supplied
for interest only. It is not necessary to understand these details to be
able to use this filtering option in Scion.

===========================================================================
Extract from Practical Algorithms for Programmers by Andrew Binstock and
John Rex. Addison-Wesley Publishing Co. ISBN 0-201-63208-X.
===========================================================================

Rather than simply coding letters based on their approximate sound,
Metaphone uses a series of rules to transform one sound into another.
Unlike Soundex, it does not restrict itself to consonants, but rather
examines groups of letters known as diphthongs.

Metaphone removes non-alphabetic characters from the search key and
converts the remaining letters to uppercase as shown in the table below.
It then discards all vowels, unless the word begins with a vowel, in which
case the vowel is retained. The remaining consonants are mapped to their
Metaphone code, with two additions: the letter X represents the "sh"
sound, and the digit 0 represents the "th" sound. If any of the
consonants except C are doubled, the second consonant is removed. The table
below shows the transformations.

Transformations performed by Metaphone -

From              To
=======================================================================
GN- KN- PN-       N
AE-               E
WH-               H
WR-               R
X-                S
B                 B (unless in -MB)
C                 X if in -CIA-, -CH-
                    else S if in -CI-, -CE-, -CY-
                    else dropped if in -SCI-, -SCE-, -SCY-
                    else K
D                 J if in -DGE-, -DGI-, -DGY-
                    else T
G                 F if in -GH and not B--GH, D--GH, -H--GH, -H---GH
                    else dropped if -GNED, -GN, -DGE-, -DGI-, or -DGY-
                    else J if in -GE-, -GI -GY, and not GG
                    else K
H                 H if before a vowel and not after C, G, P, S, T
K                 dropped if after C, else K
P                 F if before H, else P
Q                 K
S                 X in -SIO- or -SIA-, else S
T                 X in -TIA- or -TIO-
                    else O before H
                    else T
V                 F
W                 W after vowel, else dropped
X                 KS
Y                 Y unless followed by vowel
Z                 S
F, J, L, M, N, R  never transformed

As can be readily seen, Metaphone performs much more specific
transformations on words than does Soundex. Notice that the
transformations very closely fit the way English is spoken. For
example, B is left alone unless it appears as part of the -MB
combination at the end of a word (such as bomb or comb), where it is
silent. The sequence PH is compressed into an F (meaning that haphazard
will not be correctly found -- but how specific can the rules be made
without creating a dictionary of all words?). Q is converted into K in
all cases (recall that the U that invariably succeeds Q has already been
removed), which rightly results in a match for cake and quake or kick
and quick, and so forth. Soundex, unlike Metaphone, cannot handle the
possibility of special cases at all. It converts PH into a P sound,
which is then lumped with all B and V sounds. The result of Metaphone's
greater specificity is that Metaphone tends to be more accurate than
Soundex in its searches, since the words are better encoded.

============================== End of extract ============================

The original routine was specifically designed for English. This version
has been modified for Scion to add a degree of "internationalisation".
The following new character mappings have been added:

 From         To
-------------------
 Ū, ń, ▀       S
 ą, ­, ▐, ■    0 (corresponding to "th" sound)
 č, ±          N

All other "hi-bit" characters above $C0 ('└') are considered to be vowels.
Those hi-bit characters below $C0 ('└') are discarded.

These modifications are by no way complete. For example, the German 'w'
is NOT handled correctly, as will be some others. A totally language
independent "soundex" is virtually an impossibility!
@ENDNODE

##
## "Date Requesters" - Displayed as help on all types of date requesters
##

@NODE DateReq "Date Requesters"
                            Date Requesters

Clicking on any date field (gadget) will raise a date requester. This
requester is then used to establish the event date.

The actual date part consists of three fields -

	(1) Day   - Enter the day number. Eg '23' for "23 March 1879"
	(2) Month - Enter the month either as a month number or a
	            month abbreviation. Eg For "23 March 1879", you can
		    enter either '3' (for "March") or 'Mar' (as an
		    abbreviation for "March"). When you move away from
		    the Month field, it will be automatically updated
		    to show the month abbreviation.
	(3) Year  - Enter the COMPLETE year of the event. For example,
		    enter '1879', NOT '79' - after all, the century is
		    important!

Valid dates are "year only", "month and year" and "day, month and year".
Any other combinations are illegal (and meaningless).

The requester will check that the entered date is completely valid, and
re-position the cursor to the "offending" field if an error is made. For
example, it will check the number of days in the entered month, and do
leap-year checking.

The entered date may then be further "qualified". To the left of the "Day"
field, there is a "Qualify" gadget that allows you to indicate whether the
date is "Before", "After" or "Circa" the entered date. Click on this gadget
to select the appropriate choice. Choose "None" if the date is an exact
date.  Note that this gadget does not appear in the date requesters raised
in the "Search" requesters.

If the date is a "Before Christ" date, check the "BC" checkbox to the right
of the "Year" field.

If the date is uncertain (maybe the date has been deduced from other
information, but has not been verified against actual records) check the
"Uncertain" checkbox in the bottom-left of the requester.  Note that this
gadget does not appear in the date requesters raised in the "Search"
requesters.

If a mistake is made entering the date, clicking on the "Clear" button
in the bottom-right of the requester will clear the entered date.

Choosing "Accept" will close the requester, and enter the date into the
appropriate field. Choosing "Cancel" will close the requester without
making any changes to the date in the actual field.

The <ESC> key will also end input into any date field, so you don't have to
take your hands off the keyboard. For example, enter the date, press <ESC>
to end entry of data into one of the date string gadgets, and then press
'A' for "Accept".

SUGGESTIONS:
(1) Where an event date is known to be within a range (such as between 1876
and 1879), enter the FIRST date in the appropriate date field, and make
a note in the "comments" field about the possible range.

(2) Where the day and month (but not the year) of an event is known, either
estimate the year and mark the date as 'circa', or record the partial date
in the 'comments' field.

See also @{" Dates " LINK DateField}  @{" Death Date " LINK DeathDate}  @{" Ended Date " LINK EndedDate}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Name Pick Requester" - Displayed as help on name pick requesters
##

@NODE PickReq "Name Pick Requester"
			  Last Name Pick List

Every time that the <RETURN> or <TAB> key is pressed while in the Last Name
entry field, that last name is checked against a list of names maintained
in the "Last Name Pick List". If the current name is unique, it is added to
that pick list. This list maintains the 14 most recent unique last names
entered.

To transfer a last name from the pick list into the Last Name entry field,
simply click on the appropriate name in the list. That name will then be
transferred into the Last Name field where it may be accepted or edited.

This reduces the amount of typing required, and also ensures consistent
spelling of last names.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Family Note Viewer/Editor Gadget"
##

@NODE FamilyEditor "Family Note Viewer/Editor Gadget"
                            View/Edit Notes Gadget

Clicking on this gadget will VIEW a family note. SHIFT-clicking on this
gadget will EDIT a family note.

Clicking on the "View/Edit Notes" gadget will either display/edit an
attached note (an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately
to the right of the gadget), or raise a file requester where you can enter
the name of the free-form note that you wish to view/edit. The viewer or
editor that will be used is defined using the @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer} and
@{" Choose Notes Editor " LINK ChooseEditor} options under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu. If no Notes
Viewer is defined, the internal notes viewer will be used.

See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.

By default the notes are assigned the name FNx.database, where "FN" stands
for "Family Notes", "x" is the FGRN of the current family displayed, and
"database" is the name of the database. The name of the database is defined
when you save the database.

The default name can be ignored, and the notes file can be given any name.
(Note that the "pattern" field in the file requester may have to be
changed so that you can see files with other than the default names. Enter
#? as the pattern to see ALL files.)

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "1" for viewing, "!" for editing.
@ENDNODE

##
## "View Family Picture Gadget"
##

@NODE ViewFamily "View Family Picture Gadget"
                            View Picture Gadget

Clicking on the "ViewPicture" gadget will either display an attached
picture (an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately to the
right of the gadget), or raise a file requester where you can enter the
name of the IFF picture file that you wish to view. The viewer that will
used will either be Scion's in-built viewer or a user-defined viewer
defined using the @{" Choose Viewer " LINK ChooseViewer} option under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.

By default the pictures are assigned the name FPx.database, where "FP"
stands for "Family Picture", "x" is the FGRN of the current family
displayed, and "database" is the name of the database. The name of the
database is defined when you save the database.

The default name can be ignored, and the picture file can be given any
name.  (Note that the "pattern" field in the file requester may have to be
changed so that you can see files with other than the default names. Enter
#? as the pattern to see ALL files.)

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "2".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Family Search Gadget"
##

@NODE FamilySearch "Family Search Gadget"
                        Family Search gadget

                       Keyboard shortcut is "+"

This gadget allows you to search for a particular family in the database.

After clicking on the "Family Search" gadget you will be presented with a
requester asking for "Last Name", "First Names", "Place" and "Date Range".
Type the name of name of the person whose marriages you are trying to find
into the "name" fields. To limit the search to a particular place of
engagement, marriage, or ending, enter a place-name into the "place" field.
Note that Scion will search all these event place fields to find a match
for the "place" entered. To further limit the search to a date range, enter
"start" and "end" dates into the appropriate date fields. If no "start"
date is entered, Scion will search for any date up to any specified "end"
date.  If no "end" date is entered, Scion will search for all dates later
than any specified "start" date. Therefore, if no "start" or "end" dates
are entered, Scion will ignore dates while searching.

Click on "Find First" to find (and display) the Family Details Window for
the first marriage in the database matching your entries.

On first starting the programme, the Last Name and First Name(s) and Place
fields will contain ".*". This represents a @{" Regular Expression " LINK Regex} matching
ANY person and place in the database. In this (default) case, clicking on
"Find Next" will take you to the Family Details Window for the next family
in FGRN numerical order.

If the search fields already contain the name(s), etc that you want (from a
previous search) click on "Find Next" to move to the Family Details Window
for the next family in the database matching your entries, or click on
"Find Prev" to move to the Family Details Window for the previous family
in the database matching your entries.

When you have located the family of interest, clicking "Cancel" will remove
the search requester from display.

If the screen flashes when carrying out a search, that means that there are
no more matching entries in the database.

NOTE: You can search for event place names ONLY by entering the ".*"
      pattern into the personal name fields, and the place of interest
      into the "Place" field. Scion will then search for any record
      matching this place-name in the engagement, marriage or ended place
      fields.

      Similarly, by entering ".*" into the Place field as well, and
      entering a "start" date and an "end" date, Scion will search for all
      records with an engagement, marriage or ended date within that range.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Set Spouse Gadget"
##

@NODE AddSpouse "Set Spouse Gadget"
			      Set Spouse Gadget

To add a Spouse to a family group when there is no spouse already defined,
(thereby establishing a "marriage" between the Principal and the Spouse),
click on the "Set Spouse" gadget. A list of all the people in the
database will be displayed.

   See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on
   the "filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

   Click on the Spouse you wish to add to the family group. The selected
   Spouse will then be displayed near the top of the Family Details Window.

   Selecting "Cancel" from the list of people displayed will abort this
   operation.

If there is already a spouse defined for the family group, and you wish
to delete or change that spouse (maybe you had the wrong person), clicking
on the "Set Spouse" gadget will ask if you wish to remove the existing
spouse and (optionally) replace with a new spouse. If you select "yes",
the existing spouse will be removed, a list of all the people in the
database will be displayed, and you can select the "replacement" spouse
as outlined above.

If, at this point, you select the "Cancel" gadget in the list of people,
the original spouse will have been removed (deleting them from the family
group).

   If you wish to re-instate a deleted spouse to the family group, click
   on the "Set Spouse" gadget again and add them to the family group
   as outlined above.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "4".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Add Child Gadget"
##

@NODE AddChild "Add Child Gadget"
			     Add Child Gadget

To add one or more children to a family group (thereby establishing
the Principal and Spouse as the childrens' parents), click on the "Add
Child" gadget. A list of all the people in the database WITHOUT parents
will be displayed. (When memory is getting low, it is possible that ALL
people will be displayed - not just parent-less people. In this situation,
people who already have parents will be "ghosted" and it will not be
possible to select these "ghosted" entries.)

See @{" filtering and pattern matching " LINK Filtering} and @{" list sorting " LINK Sorting} for details on the
"filtering" and "sorting" gadgets available in this list.

Click on the children you wish to add to the family group. To "de-select"
a child selected accidentally, click on the child's name again. Note that
you also use the menu to "select all displayed" or to "clear all selected".

When you are satisfied with the list of selected children, click on the
"Accept" gadget and the children will be added to the family group.

The added children will then be displayed in the list of children in the
Family Details Window (in birth date order).

Selecting "Cancel" from the list of people displayed will abort this
operation.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "5".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Remove Child Gadget"
##

@NODE RemoveChild "Remove Child Gadget"
                           Remove Child Gadget

To remove a child from a family group:

    (1) Highlight the child to be removed by clicking on the chosen child
        in the "Children" list in the Family Details Window. The selected
	child will then be displayed in the position below the list. The
	"Remove Child" gadget will then be enabled.

    (2) Click on the "Remove Child" gadget. You will be asked to confirm
        that you wish to remove the child from the family group. Replying
	"no" will cancel the operation. Replying "yes" will remove the
	child from the family group.

The child removed will become an "orphan".

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "6".
@ENDNODE

##
## "Dissolve Family Gadget"
##

@NODE DissolveFamily "Dissolve Family Gadget"
                          Dissolve Family Gadget

To remove a family from the database, click on the "Dissolve Family"
gadget.  You will be asked to confirm your actions before the record is
actually removed.  Not only will the family's Family Details Window data be
deleted, but ALL references to that family will also be removed. Children
specified as part of the family group will become "orphans", and the
original Principal and Spouse will be "divorced".

WARNING: Once you have removed a family from the database, the
         information is irretrievably lost, and the original FGRN and
         corresponding Family Details Window are available for
	 reassignment.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "7".
@ENDNODE

##
## "New Marriage Gadget"
##

@NODE NewMarriage "New Marriage Gadget"
                          "New Marriage Gadget"

This gadget allows you to establish additional marriages (family groups)
for the current Principal. Clicking on this gadget will, after
confirmation, display a new Family Details Window corresponding to a new
marriage for the Principal. A spouse and children may now be added to
this family group as for the first marriage.

(To move between marriages, use the "marriage navigation" gadgets at the
bottom-left of the Family Details Window.)

If this gadget is "ghosted" (shaded grey), it means that the Principal has
already been married for the maximum number of times permitted, and this
gadget will do nothing.

The keyboard shortcut for this gadget is "8".
@ENDNODE

@REMARK Menus Stuff **********************************************************

##
## "Project Menu"
##

@NODE ProjectMenu "Project Menu"
                            "Project" Menu

The following functions are available from the "Project" menu:

   @{" New        " LINK MenuNew}
   @{" Open...    " LINK MenuOpen}
   @{" Save       " LINK MenuQuickSave}
   @{" Save As... " LINK MenuSave}
   @{" Info...    " LINK MenuInfo}
@REMARK %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%   @{" GEDCOM...  " LINK InbuiltGEDCOM}
   @{" About...   " LINK MenuAbout}
   @{" Help       " LINK MyMenuHelp}
   @{" Iconify    " LINK MenuIconify}
   @{" Quit       " LINK MenuQuit}
@ENDNODE

##
## "New"
##

@NODE MenuNew "New"
Project/New:

Selecting "New" will, after requesting confirmation, delete the existing
database.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Open..."
##

@NODE MenuOpen "Open..."
Project/Open...

Selecting "Open..." will, after requesting confirmation, display a
standard file requester. Select the database you wish to load, and
click on the "Open" gadget to bring that database into Scion
Genealogist. If you do not wish to load the selected database, click on
the "Cancel" gadget.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Save"
##

@NODE MenuQuickSave "Save"
Project/Save:

Selecting "Save" will save the existing database immediately to disk
without asking for confirmation or whether you wish to overwrite an
existing copy of that database.

NOTE: When you save a database using the @{" Save As... " LINK MenuSave} option, the
      filename that you give the database will become the default name
      that will be used by this "Save" option.

      If there is no database name, or the database is called "Unnamed",
      this "Save" option will ask that you name the database first.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Save As..."
##

@NODE MenuSave "Save As..."
Project/Save As...

Selecting "Save As..." will, after requesting confirmation, display a
standard file requester. Select the database you wish to save (or type
in the name for a new database file) and click on the "Save" gadget to
save that database. If you do not wish to save the database, click on
the "Cancel" gadget.

NOTE: When you save a database, the filename that you give the database
      will become the default name for the database. If you do not
      enter a database file name, the database name will default to
      "Unnamed".
@ENDNODE

##
## "GEDCOM..."
##

@NODE InbuiltGEDCOM "GEDCOM..."
Project/GEDCOM...

This menu option allows you to import or export GEDCOM files.

This option is not currently implemented. In the meantime, please use the
supplied AREXX scripts. See @{" GEDCOM Support " LINK GEDCOM} for more information.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Info..."
##

@NODE MenuInfo "Info..."
Project/Info...

Selecting "Info..." will display a requester containing the following
information:

Project name:      The name set when you save a database, see @{" Save As... " LINK MenuSave},
                   otherwise will be "unnamed"
Date last saved:   The date that the currently loaded database was last
                   saved. Note that databases created with earlier versions
		   of Scion will not display a "last saved" date.
Nnumber of people: The current number of people.
Number of families: The current number of families.

Notes editor:      The name of your selected notes editor.
                   See @{" Choose Notes Editor " LINK ChooseEditor}.
Notes viewer:      The name of your selected notes viewer.
                   See @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}.
                   In the absence of a user-defined viewer, Scion will
		   attempt to use its own "internal" viewer.
Pictures viewer:   The name of your selected picture viewer.
                   See @{" Choose Picture Viewer " LINK ChooseViewer}.
                   In the absence of a user-defined viewer, Scion will
		   attempt to use its own "internal" viewer.
Sound player:      The name of your selected sound sample player.
                   See @{" Choose Sound Player " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer}.

Programme version: The current version number of Scion Genealogist.
ARexx port name:   The ARexx port name for this instance of the programme.
Available memory:  The approximate amount of free memory remaining.
@ENDNODE

##
## "About..."
##

@NODE MenuAbout "About..."
Project/About...

Selecting "About..." will display a requester containing information about
the programme.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Help"
##

@NODE MyMenuHelp "Help"
Project/Help:

Selecting "Help" will display this help file.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Iconify"
##

@NODE MenuIconify "Iconify"
Project/Iconify:

NOTE: This menu item is only enabled while running Scion on the Workbench
      (or default public screen).

Selecting "Iconify" will remove both the Personal and Family Windows and
replace them with an icon on the Workbench (or default public screen). To
restore both windows, double-click on this icon.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Quit"
##

@NODE MenuQuit "Quit"
Project/Quit:

Selecting "Quit" will, after requesting confirmation, exit the programme.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Print Menu"
##

@NODE PrintMenu "Print Menu"
                            "Print" Menu

The following functions are available from the "Print" menu:

   @{" Set Print Options     " LINK PrintPrefsReq}
   @{" List of People        " LINK PrintPeople}
   @{" Personal Summary      " LINK PrintSummary}
   @{" List of Relatives     " LINK PrintBlood}
   @{" Pedigree Chart        " LINK PrintPedigree}
   @{" Ahnentafel Chart      " LINK PrintAhnentafel}
   @{" Forefathers Chart     " LINK PrintForefathers}
   @{" Descendant Chart      " LINK PrintDescendant}
   @{" Progeny Chart         " LINK PrintProgeny}

   @{" List of Families      " LINK PrintFamilies}
   @{" Family Group Sheet    " LINK PrintFGS}

   @{" Chronology Chart      " LINK PrintChronology}
   @{" Same-Date-Events List " LINK PrintSameDate}
   @{" List of Anniversaries " LINK PrintAnniv}
   @{" Address Book          " LINK PrintAddressBook}

@ENDNODE

##
## "Set Print Options" - Displayed as help on print preferences requester
##

@NODE PrintPrefsReq "Set Print Options"
                            "Set Print Options"

The print options available from the requester are -

(1) Print to printer
        Sends the report to the printer

(2) Print to screen
        Sends the report to the screen using either the "notes viewer"
	specified in the @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer} option under the
	@{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu, or Scion's in-built notes viewer.

(3) Print to plain text file
        When this option is active, printing a report will display a
	standard file requester. Enter the name of the file that you
	want the report output directed to. The file generated will be
	plain ASCII text and can be imported into any text editor, and
	most word processors.

(4) Print to ANSI text file
        When this option is active, printing a report will display a
	standard file requester. Enter the name of the file that you
	want the report output directed to. The file generated will be
	in ANSI format. This is the same format that is sent to the
	printer and contains the ANSI printer codes for 'bold',
	'underline', etc. This file can be sent directly to the PRT:
	device and can be viewed by most Amiga text viewers.

(5) Print to RTF file
        When this option is active, printing a report will display a
	standard file requester. Enter the name of the file that you
	want the report output directed to. The file generated will be
	in RTF (Rich Text Format) format. This type of file contains all
	the information about 'bold', 'underline', etc, and can be
	loaded directly into most "top-line" word-processors such as
	FinalWriter and Microsoft Word. This format will also attempt to
	set the paper size in the word-processor to the same size as
	selected in the Workbench Printer Preferences programme.

(6) Print to HTML file
        When this option is active, printing a report will display a
	standard file requester. Enter the name of the file that you
	want the report output directed to. The file generated will be
	in HTML (HyperText Markup Language) format and can be viewed by
	most "Web Browsers" such as Netscape, Explorer, Voyager,
	Mosaic, etc.

        TIP: It is recommended that you set your page width (using the
	     Workbench Printer Preferences programme) to 75-80 characters
	     wide. Then the file can be viewed in a Web Browser without
	     having to scroll the display left/right to see the whole page.

(7) Print to AmigaGuide file
        When this option is active, printing a report will display a
	standard file requester. Enter the name of the file that you
	want the report output directed to. The file generated will be
	in "amigaguide" format and can be viewed using AmigaGuide or
	Multiview.

        TIP: It is recommended that you set your page width (using the
	     Workbench Printer Preferences programme) to about 75
	     characters wide. Then the file can be viewed in Amigaguide
	     or Multiview without having to scroll the display
	     left/right to see the whole page.

(8) Suppress IRN/FGRN's
        When checked, IRN's and FGRN's will be omitted from printed
	reports.

(9) Print attached note
        When checked, attached note file will be appended to Personal
	Summary reports (attached personal note) and Family Group Sheets
	(attached family note).

	See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}

(10) Print preparer's details
	When checked, the report preparer's name, address and telephone
	number will be appended to the reports.

	See also @{" Preparer " LINK SetPreparer}.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Print List of People"
##

@NODE PrintPeople "Print List of People"
Print/Print List of People:

This menu item will print a list of the people currently defined in the
database.

The list can be printed in numerical order (by IRN), in alphabetical order,
in order of Birth (plus baptism) Date, or in order of Death (plus burial)
Date.

When the list is sorted by date, some lines may end up with (apparently) no
date. This is because the Birth Date order list (for example) is sorted by
birth AND baptism date. Therefore, if there is no birth date but there IS a
baptism date, the person is collated by the baptism date, but when printed
out the birth date doesn't exist, and the "Born" field of the report will
be empty. Hence the apparent 'strange' sorting.  Observe the report title -
it says that the names are sorted by 'birth/baptism' (for example), NOT
just birth date. A similar situation applies for death/burial order.

Printing can be aborted at any time.

Example:
=======

List of People (Order: Alphabetical)

Project Name: Example
Report Printed On: 17 Jan 1998                                    Page: 1
=========================================================================
IRN Name of Person               Sex     Born           Died      Parents
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
108 ADAMS, Amanda Helen           F    19 May 1980                105 106
107 ADAMS, Anthony David          M    26 Jun 1956                104 103
104 ADAMS, David James            M    14 Jul 1926                       
105 ADAMS, Paul Raymond           M    19 May 1953                104 103
63  ANDERSON, Helen               F                                      
41  ANDERSON, Mary                F     1 Sep 1882    31 Mar 1958  52  53

... etc...
@ENDNODE

##
## "Print Personal Summary"
##

@NODE PrintSummary "Print Personal Summary"
Print/Print Personal Summary:

This menu item will print a detailed summary of all the information in
the database about the specified person.

The "Current" option will print details on the current person.

The "Selected..." option will display a requester where you can select the
people you wish to print personal summaries for. Note that this requester
has a menu that allows you to select all the people displayed in the
list. This is useful for printing all the items in a "filtered" list.

The "All" option will print personal summaries for all people in the
database.

If the "Print attached note" option in the @{" Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq} requester is
set, the personal note file attached to the person will be appended to the
printed report. When printing attached notes, no notice is taken of the
length of the text lines. The lines are simply read directly from the text
file and "dumped" unmodified to the output. That is, the programme will do
no word-wrapping.  Make sure that the text line lengths are <= than the
paper width otherwise the printer will issue apparently spurious carriage
returns. This method of handling also means that notes MUST be written by a
text editor, NOT a word processor!

Printing can be aborted at any time.

Example:
=======

Personal Summary 5: Caroline Mary MATHEWS

Project Name: Example
Report Printed On: 17 Jan 1998                                    Page: 1
=========================================================================
IRN:        5
Sex:        F
Born:       Aug 1879?      Place: Thomastown, Victoria, Australia
Baptised:                  Place: 
Died:       3 Mar 1962     Place: Coronation Hospital, Christchurch, NZ
Buried:     5 Mar 1962     Place: Park Cemetery, Rangiora, NZ
Occupation: 
Education:  
Religion:   
Died Of:    
Comments:   Refs: Marriage Certificate, Death Certificate
References: 
Parents:    Robert John MATHEWS [8]
            Eliza Ann WILSON [9] Age: 82? (Deceased), Marriages: 1,
Children: 4, Siblings: 8
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
FGRN:4 Spouse: Donald Gordon SMITH [4] Married: 17 May 1913
=========================================================================
@ENDNODE

##
## "Print Personal Summary"
##

@NODE PrintBlood "Print List of Relatives"
Print/Print List of Relatives:

This menu item will print a list of the relatives of the specified person.

NOTE: This report prints only BLOOD relatives. It will NOT include spouses
      of blood relatives.

The "Current" option will print the relatives of the current person.

The "Selected..." option will display a requester where you can select the
people you wish to print a list of relatives for. Note that this requester
has a menu that allows you to select all the people displayed in the
list. This is useful for printing all the items in a "filtered" list.

The "All" option will print lists of relatives for all people in the
database.

See also @{" Query Blood Relationship " link "QueryBlood"} for details about 'relationships'.

NOTE: This report requires a lot of work, so can be slow at printing.
      Please be patient.

Printing can be aborted at any time.

Example:
=======

List of Relatives 1: Albert Henry SMITH

Project Name: Example
Report Printed On: 17 Jan 1998                                    Page: 1
=========================================================================
ADAMS, Amanda Helen [108]: 2░ Cousin, 2░ Removed. Closest Common
       Ancestor: Charles Alfred SMITH [6]
ADAMS, Anthony David [107]: 2░ Cousin, 1░ Removed. Closest Common
       Ancestor: Charles Alfred SMITH [6]
ADAMS, Paul Raymond [105]: 2░ Cousin, 1░ Removed. Closest Common
       Ancestor: Charles Alfred SMITH [6]
ANDERSON, Helen [63]: 2░ Great Grandmother.
BLISS, Selina Julia [61]: 2░ Great Grandmother.
BURCHELL, Ann [55]: 2░ Great Grandmother.
CLARKSON, Wilma Henrietta [3]: Mother.
DONALD, Margaret [7]: Great Grandmother.
DONALD, Peter [62]: 2░ Great Grandfather.
IRWIN, Edwin [56]: 3░ Great Grandfather.
IRWIN, Eliza [11]: 2░ Great Grandmother.
JACKSON, Benjamin [92]: 1░ Cousin, 1░ Removed. Closest Common Ancestor:
         Donald Gordon SMITH [4]

...etc...
@ENDNODE

##
## "Print Pedigree Chart"
##

@NODE PrintPedigree "Print Pedigree Chart"
Print/Print Pedigree Chart:

This menu item will print a multi-page Pedigree Chart for the current
person. Charts are limited to 32 generations (about 600 years by most
calculations).

NOTE: Sex-less people will "break" Pedigree Charts. Hence nobody will
      appear "above" sexless people.

Printing can be aborted at any time.

