##
## "Print List of Anniversaries"
##

@NODE PrintAnniv "Print List of Anniversaries"
Print/Print List of Anniversaries:

Prints a chronological list of events.

Events supported are births (or baptisms), deaths (or burials), and
marriages (or engagements).

Baptisms, burials and engagements are only included when there are no
birth, death or wedding dates available, and the use of these alternative
dates is indicated by an '*' character in the left-most column of the
report.

Printing can be aborted at any time.

Example:
=======

List of Anniversaries (Birth/Baptism Date)

Project Name: Example
Report Printed On: 17 Jan 1998                                    Page: 1
=========================================================================
      8 Jan 1877 Ernest Alfred SMITH [37]
      9 Jan 1974 David Peter SMITH [73]
     14 Jan 1917 John Donald SMITH [31]
     17 Jan 1921 Wilma Henrietta CLARKSON [3]
     29 Jan 1925 Margaret Ellen SMITH [103]

     14 Feb 1919 Hamilton Robert SMITH [2]
     21 Feb 1948 Kaylene Maree SMITH [72]
*    22 Feb 1914 Charles Allan SMITH [29]
     28 Feb 1959 Roger Dean SMITH [70]

... etc ...

@ENDNODE

##
## "Print Address Book"
##

@NODE PrintAddressBook "Print Address Book"
Print/Print Address Book

Prints a personal or family address (and telephone) list.

Personal lists are printed in alphabetical order, and family lists are
printed (if possible) in male-partner-name alphabetical order.

Printing can be aborted at any time.

Example:
=======

Address Book (Personal)

Project Name: Example
Report Printed On: 17 Jan 1998                                    Page: 1
=========================================================================

- D -

Joan Helen DOE
427 Nowhere Avenue
Waikikamukau
NEW ZEALAND
+64 +49 123-4567

- S -

Albert Henry SMITH
5 Something Street
Cityville
Arizona
UNITED STATES
+1 +555 555-1234

... etc ...

@ENDNODE

##
## "Prefs Menu"
##

@NODE PrefsMenu "Settings Menu"
                             Settings Menu

The following functions are available from the "Settings" menu:

     @{" Choose Notes Editor    " LINK ChooseEditor}
     @{" Choose Notes Viewer    " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}
     @{" Choose Pictures Viewer " LINK ChooseViewer}
     @{" Choose Sound Player    " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer}
     @{" Set Behaviour          " LINK SetBehaviour}
     @{" Set Name Exceptions    " LINK Exceptions}
     @{" Set Function Keys      " LINK SetFunctionKeys}
     @{" Preparer               " LINK SetPreparer}
     @{" Colours                " LINK Colours}
     @{" Import                 " LINK ImportPrefs}

@ENDNODE

##
## "Choose Notes Editor"
##

@NODE ChooseEditor "Choose Notes Editor"
Settings/Choose Notes Editor:

This allows you to choose the editor to use to create and edit "free-form"
notes.

Selecting this item will display a standard file requester. Select the
editor that you wish to use, and then click on "Use It" in the requester.
The editor that you choose is remembered when you save a database, and will
be restored when that database is re-loaded.

@{" Tested Editors " LINK TestedEditors}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Choose Notes Viewer"
##

@NODE ChooseNotesViewer "Choose Notes Viewer"
Settings/Choose Notes Viewer:

By default, Scion will attempt to locate the default Workbench text viewer
and use that to display standard ASCII text files. For AmigaOS 2.1 (or
earlier) this will be "More", and for AmigaOS 3.0 (or later) this will be
"Multiview".If Scion cannot locate this viewer, it will use its own
"internal" text viewer instead. This internal viewer will attempt to use
the "System Default Font" that you have set using the Workbench
"Prefs/Font" programme.

The internal viewer is very basic and does NOT include features such as
word-wrapping, searching or printing. However, you can use this option to
choose another text viewer to use to view any notes you may have. 

The chosen text viewer is also used to view "free-form" notes and any
"print-to-screen" reports. See also @{" Set Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq}.

Selecting this item will display a standard file requester. Select the text
viewer that you wish to use, and then click on "Use It" in the requester.
The text viewer that you choose is remembered when you save a database, and
will be restored when that database is re-loaded.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Choose Picture Viewer"
##

@NODE ChooseViewer "Choose Picture Viewer"
Settings/Choose Picture Viewer:

By default, Scion will attempt to locate the default Workbench picture
viewer and use that to display standard IFF-ILBM pictures. For AmigaOS 2.1
(or earlier) this will be "Display", and for AmigaOS 3.0 (or later) this
will be "Multiview". If Scion cannot locate this viewer, it will use its
own "internal" picture viewer instead.

However, you can use this option to choose another picture viewer to use to
view any pictures you may have.

Selecting this item will display a standard file requester. Select the
viewer that you wish to use, and then click on "Use It" in the requester.
The viewer that you choose is remembered when you save a database, and will
be restored when that database is re-loaded.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Choose Sound Player"
##

@NODE ChooseSoundPlayer "Choose Sound Player"
Settings/Choose Sound Player:

By default, Scion will use it's basic, internal sound player to play your
IFF-8SVX sound files.

This option allows you to choose the sound file player to use as an
alternative (maybe your sound files are of a different format).

Selecting this item will display a standard file requester. Select the
sound player that you wish to use, and then click on "Use It" in the
requester.  The player that you choose is remembered when you save a
database, and will be restored when that database is re-loaded.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Set Behaviour"
##

@NODE SetBehaviour "Set Behaviour"
Settings/Set Behaviour:

This allows you to control some of the behaviour of the programme.

(1) Confirm "Add Person"
    By default, the programme will always ask you to confirm if you wish
    to add a new person when you click on the "Add New Person" gadget or
    select the "Add People" menu item.

    When the Confirm "Add Person" checkbox is ticked, this is the
    behaviour that will occur. If the chechbox is NOT ticked, the
    programme will NOT ask you to confirm if you wish to add a new
    person or "bulk add" people.

(2) Capitalize first names
    By default, the programme will force all names in a "first name(s)"
    field to lower-case with the initial letter of every name capitalized.
    When the "Capitalize first names" checkbox is ticked, this is the
    behaviour that will occur. If the checkbox is NOT ticked, any entries
    in a "first name(s)" field will be left as typed.

(3) Capitalize event place names
    By default, the programme performs NO processing of the data entered
    into an event place field (for example, Birth Place). When the
    "Capitalize event place names" checkbox is ticked, the programme will
    set the initial letter of every word to a capital letter. All other
    letters are unchanged. If the checkbox is NOT ticked, any entries in
    an "event place" field will be left as typed.

(4) Carry-over last names
    By default, when a new person is added to the database (using the
    "Add New Person" gadget), the Last Name field will be blank. If the
    "Carry-over last names" checkbox is ticked, the programme will fill
    in the Last Name field of a new person with the last name of the
    most recently displayed person. This shortcut is often useful when
    adding a number of people with the same last name. When the checkbox
    is NOT ticked, any new person added will start out with a blank
    Last Name field.

    See also the @{" Pick " LINK PickName} gadget.

(5) List sort "pop-up" gadget
    By default, Scion uses a standard "cycle" type gadget in the bottom
    left-hand corner of displayed lists to select different sort-orders.

    Because Scion has to re-sort the lists for every new choice, it means
    that on some slower Amigas, or with large databases, that it can take
    some seconds to cycle between choices (while the re-sorting is carried
    out).

    To reduce this delay, select this option to turn the gadget into a
    "pop-up" type gadget. This type of gadget, when clicked, will show you
    a selection of the sort options available. Move the mouse cursor over
    the sort-order of choice and release the mouse button. Scion will then
    move directly to the new sort-order without stepping through
    intermediate choices.

(6) Scion default public screen
    A public screen is a screen that allow other applications to open
    their display windows on that screen instead of the Workbench screen.

    By default, the Amiga's default public screen is the Workbench screen.
    Selecting this option makes the Scion screen the default public screen
    instead.

    Scion's public screen name is the same as the ARexx port name. See
    @{" ARexx Interface " LINK AREXXIntro} for further information.

(7) "Shanghai" windows
    If this option is selected, older application programmes which expect
    to open their windows on the Workbench screen will open their
    windows instead on the default pubic screen (which may or may not
    be the Scion screen - see (6) above).

(8) Pop screen to front
    If this option is selected, the Scion screen will be "popped" to the
    front when a window opens on it.

(9) "Snapshot" window positions
    By default Scion will open the Personal and Family Details windows
    in the top left-hand corner of the screen. If you move the windows
    to new positions, and wish to have Scion re-position the windows to
    the new locations everytime a database is loaded, tick this option.

@ENDNODE

##
##  "Set Name Exceptions"
##

@NODE Exceptions "Set Name Exceptions"
Settings/Set Name Exceptions

This allows you to maintain a list of Last Names that should not be fully
capitalised. For example, MacDONALD may be preferred over MACDONALD. Scion
will automatically choose the correct capitalisation of a Last Name from
this list.

Selecting this item will display a list of currently defined Name
Exceptions.

To add a new name to the list, type the name as you wish it to be
capitalised (for example, MacDONALD) into the entry field near the bottom
of the list and then press <enter>. The name will now be displayed in the
list above.

To change an existing entry in the list, click on the name in the main list
area. The name will now be displayed in the entry field near the bottom
of the list. Type the corrections required, and then press <enter>. The
changed name will be added back to the main list.

To delete an entry in the list, click on the name in the main list area.
The name will now be displayed in the entry field near the bottom of the
list. Click on the "Delete" button. The name has now been removed from the
list.

When you are satisfied with the contents of the Name Exception list, click
on the "Accept" button.
@ENDNODE

##
##  "Set Function Keys"
##

@NODE SetFunctionKeys "Set Function Keys"
Settings/Set Function Keys

This allows you to define operations that can be carried out using the
Amiga function keys F1...F10, and the shift/alt/ctrl'd function keys, for
a total of 40 different function key assignments.

Typically these keys could be used to issue ARexx commands, although any
valid command can be attached to a function key.

Type in the commands you want executed into the appropriate string
gadget(s) for the required function key(s) and then click on the "Accept"
button. To cancel out of the operation, click the "Cancel" button.

Example:
=======

Entering "rx REXX:Scion2GEDCOM" into the "F1" entry gadget will mean that
the Arexx programme "Scion2GEDCOM.rexx" will be run any time the F1
function key is pressed.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Preparer"
##

@NODE SetPreparer "Preparer"
Settings/Preparer:

This menu item allows you to enter name, address and telephone details of
the person preparing the database. These details can be (optionally)
appended to printed reports. See also @{" Set Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq}.

If the number of lines displayed in the requester does not provide enough
fields, each line can contain more than a single item. For example, the
first address line could contain something like - "Ettrick Cottage, 42 High
Street". Each "component" entered on a single line should be separated by a
comma. Do NOT add a comma at the end of each line - Scion will append this
automatically.

Similarly, if you wish to record a FAX number or an email address, add
these to the "telephone" line as in the following example -

    "+64 +4 555-9876, FAX: 555-1234, email: jdoe@provider.net"

In this example, "+64 +4 555-9876" is the telephone number. The FAX and
email details are appended to this.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Import Settings"
##

@NODE ImportPrefs "Import Settings"
Settings/Import Settings

This option lets you load all the programme settings from another Scion
version 5 (or later) database. This saves you from having to re-enter all
your favourite settings when you create a new database - you can simply
import them from an earlier database.

NOTE: This option will NOT load any settings from databases created with
      pre-version 5 versions of Scion. If an attempt is made to import
      settings from an earlier-style database, the error message "Error
      Accessing File" will be displayed.

The settings that are imported are -

  - the @{" Notes Editor     " LINK ChooseEditor}
  - the @{" Notes Viewer     " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}
  - the @{" Pictures Viewer  " LINK ChooseViewer}
  - the @{" Sound Player     " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer}
  - the @{" Behaviour Flags  " LINK SetBehaviour}
  - the @{" Name Exceptions  " LINK Exceptions}
  - the @{" Function Keys    " LINK SetFunctionKeys}
  - the @{" Preparer Details " LINK SetPreparer}
  - the @{" Colours          " LINK Colours}

In addition, the various @{" Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq} are also imported.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Colours"
##

@NODE Colours "Colours"
Settings/Colours:

This allows you to "customize" the colour of the display. To choose a
particular colour-scheme, select that colour-scheme from this menu. The
screen will immediately change colour to reflect your new choice.

The "Default" option will "clone" the colour-scheme used by your current
Workbench (as closely as possible), but will also ensure that males are
displayed in blue and females are displayed in red.

The "Workbench" option will "clone" the complete colour-scheme used by your
current Workbench. Please note that with this option, males may no longer
be displayed in blue and females may no longer be displayed in red.

The "Custom..." option will display a palette requester where you can
change the colours to anything you want.

Colours are remembered when you save a database, and will be restored when
that database is re-loaded.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Extras Menu"
##

@NODE ExtrasMenu "Extras Menu"
                            "Extras" Menu

The following functions are available from the "Extras" menu:

     @{" Attachments              " LINK Attachments}
     @{" Set address/phone        " LINK SetAddress}
     @{" Query Blood Relationship " LINK QueryBlood}
     @{" Add People               " LINK BulkPeople}
@ENDNODE

##
## "Attachments"
##

@NODE Attachments "Attachments"
Extras/Attachments:

The "Extras/Attachments" menu item allows you to "attach" notes, pictures
and/or sound files to the current personal or family record.

On selecting an "attach...", a standard file requester is displayed. Select
the item to attach to the current person/family.

The presence of an attachment is indicated by a small black dot immediately
to the right of the View/Edit Notes gadget, the View Pictures gadget and/or
the Play Sound File gadget.

The remove an existing attachment, select the "detach..." menu sub-item.

If the "Print attached note" option in the @{" Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq} requester is
set, the note file attached to the record can be appended to the Personal
Summary or FamilyGroup Sheet printed reports. When printing attached notes,
no notice is taken of the length of the text lines. The lines are simply
read directly from the text file and "dumped" unmodified to the output.
That is, the programme will do no word-wrapping.  Make sure that the text
line lengths are <= than the paper width otherwise the printer will issue
apparently spurious carriage returns. This method of handling also means
that notes MUST be written by a text editor, NOT a word processor!


@ENDNODE

##
## "Set address/phone"
##

@NODE SetAddress "Set Address/phone"
Extras/Set address/phone:

This menu item allows you to enter address and telephone details of the
current person or family.

If the number of lines displayed in the requester does not provide enough
fields, each line can contain more than a single item. For example, the
first line could contain something like - "Ettrick Cottage, 42 High
Street". Each "component" entered on a single line should be separated by a
comma. Do NOT add a comma at the end of each line - Scion will append this
automatically.

Similarly, if you wish to record a FAX number or an email address, add
these to the "telephone" line as in the following example -

    "+64 +4 555-9876, FAX: 555-1234, email: jdoe@provider.net"

In this example, "+64 +4 555-9876" is the telephone number. The FAX and
email details are appended to this.

@ENDNODE

##
## "Query Blood Relationship"
##

@NODE QueryBlood "Query Blood Relationship"
Extras/Query Blood Relationship:

This menu item allows you to query the "blood" relationship between any
person in the database and the CURRENTLY displayed person.

When selected, a list of people will be displayed. Click on the possible
relative. A requester will then be displayed showing the relationship
between the current displayed person and the person selected from the
list.

If appropriate, the nearest common male ancestor (or female ancestor, in
the absence of information about the male ancestor) will also be displayed.

NOTE: "Query Blood Relationship" checks only BLOOD relatives. It will NOT
      find spouses of blood relatives.

Explanation of returned relationships -
=====================================
   ... 2░ Cousin  - means "second cousin"
   ... 3░ Cousin  - means "third cousin"
   ... etc.

   ... 2░ Cousin, 1░ Removed  - means "second cousin, once removed"
   ... 1░ Cousin, 2░ Removed  - means "first cousin, twice removed"
   ... etc.

   ... 3░ Great Grandfather  - means "Great Great Great Grandfather"
                               (3 greats)
   ... etc.

Because "cousins" can be the source of some confusion, refer to @{" cousins " link Cousins}
for more details on the definitions used by Scion.

Nephew/niece: The son/daughter of one's brother or sister.

Grand-nephew: The son/daughter of a nephew or niece. A son's or
       daughter's nephew/niece.

Uncle/aunt: One's father's or mother's brother/sister.

Grand-uncle/aunt: One's grandfather's or grandmother's brother/sister.
       One's father's or mother's uncle/aunt.

Aren't relationships fun!

ONE FINAL NOTE: "half-brothers" and "half-sisters" (same father, different
                mother, for example) are reported simply as "brother"
		or "sister".
@ENDNODE


##
## "Cousins"
##

@NODE Cousins "Cousins"
                             Cousins
                             -------

Some definitions of "cousin" -

(1) The dictionary definition:
    First, second cousins, etc: Expresses the relationship of persons
           descended the same number of steps from a common ancestor.
           Hence, the children of first cousins are second cousins,
           and so on.

    "Removed": The number of steps away from a cousin. For example, a
           child of your first cousin is your "first cousin once
           removed", and THEIR child is your 'first cousin twice
           removed", etc.

(2) An alternate way of saying the same thing:
    - (first) cousin: a child of one's uncle or aunt.
    - first cousin once removed: a child of one's first cousin / one's
      parent's first cousin.
    - first cousin twice removed: a grandchild of one's first cousin / one's
      grandparent's first cousin.
    - second cousin: a child of one's parent's first cousin.
    - second cousin once removed: a child of one's second cousin / one's
      parent's second cousin.
    - third cousin: child of one's parent's second cousin.
    - etc, etc, etc.

And just to confuse things even more, in English, "first cousins" are
sometimes referred to as "cousins-german" or "full cousins" or even just
simply "cousins".  Scion uses the "strict" definitions outlined above.

SPECIAL NOTE: In some non-English countries, different ways are used to
              represent the degree of a cousin. Scion uses the strict
	      "English" definition above only. Sorry!

Finally, a 'graphical' representation might help:

PLEASE NOTE: All relationships are relative to "YOU".

GreatGrandParent -------------------------------- GreatGrandUncle/Aunt
      |                                                    |
      |                                                    |
  Grandparent -------------- GrandUncle/Aunt           3-cousin
      |                            |                       |
      |                            |                       |
    Parent ----- Uncle/Aunt    2-cousin                3-cousin/
      |              |             |                   1-removed
      |              |             |                       |
     YOU         1-cousin    2-cousin/1-removed        3-cousin/
                     |             |                   2-removed
                     |             |                       |
                 1-cousin/   2-cousin/2-removed         ..etc..
                 1-removed         |
                     |             |
                 1-cousin/   2-cousin/3-removed
                 2-removed         |
                     |             |
                     |          ..etc..
                  ..etc..

@ENDNODE

##
## "Add People"
##

@NODE BulkPeople "Add People"
Extras/Add People:

Instead of adding people to the database one at a time (using the "Add
Person" gadget in the Personal Details Window), you can "bulk" add space
for people by using this menu item.

There are two sub-items in this menu -

  - Make space for 10: This will add 10 "blank" people to the database,
                       if space is available.

  - Make space for 20: This will add 20 "blank" people to the database,
                       if space is available.

If the programme behaviour is set to "no confirmation" (using the
"Confirm 'Add Person'" option), the programme will not ask to confirm the
addition of the new people. See @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour}.

@ENDNODE

@REMARK Miscellaneous topics help ********************************************

##
## "Individual Record Number"
##

@NODE IRN "Individual Record Number"
                      IRN - Individual Record Number

Every person in the database is automatically assigned a unique IRN. These
numbers will NEVER change, even if people are deleted from the database. A
deleted person's IRN will be automatically reassigned whenever a new person
is added to the database.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Family Group Record Number"
##

@NODE FGRN "Family Group Record Number"
                    FGRN - Family Group Record Number

Every family in the database is automatically assigned a unique FGRN.
These numbers will NEVER change, even if families are deleted from the
database. A deleted family's FGRN will be automatically reassigned whenever
a new family is added to the database.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Free Form Notes"
##

@NODE FreeFormNotes "Free Form Notes"
                              Free Form Notes

Scion Genealogist allows you to create and edit note files of any size
using any editor of your choice. The editor to use is set up by selecting
the @{" Choose Editor " LINK ChooseEditor} option from the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

You can also simply view notes files of any size using Scion's in-built
text viewer, or any other text viewer of your choice. The viewer to use is
set up by selecting @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer} option under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

Personal notes are accessed by clicking on the @{" View/Edit Notes " LINK PersonEditor} gadget
in the Personal Details Window, and family notes are accessed by clicking
on the @{" View/Edit Notes " LINK FamilyEditor} gadget in the Family Details Window.

@{" Tested Editors " LINK TestedEditors}

If the "Print attached note" option in the @{" Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq} requester is
set, the note file attached to the person or family will be appended to the
printed report. When printing attached notes, no notice is taken of the
length of the text lines. The lines are simply read directly from the text
file and "dumped" unmodified to the output. That is, the programme will do
no word-wrapping.  Make sure that the text line lengths are <= than the
paper width otherwise the printer will issue apparently spurious carriage
returns. This method of handling also means that notes MUST be written by a
text editor, NOT a word processor!
@ENDNODE

##
## "Viewing Pictures"
##

@NODE Pictures "Viewing Pictures"
                              Viewing Pictures

Scion Genealogist allows you to view IFF picture files either using Scion's
internal picture viewer or any alternative picture viewer of your choice.
The viewer to use is set up by selecting the @{" Choose Picture Viewer " LINK ChooseViewer}
option from the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

Personal pictures are accessed by clicking on the @{" View Picture " LINK ViewPerson} gadget in
the Personal Details Window, and family pictures are accessed by clicking
on the @{" View Picture " LINK ViewFamily} gadget in the Family Details Window.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Playing Sound Files"
##

@NODE PlayingSounds "Playing Sound Files"
                           Playing Sound Files

Scion Genealogist allows you to play sound files either using Scion's
internal IFF-8SVX sound player or any other alternate sound player of your
choice. The player to use is set up by selecting the
@{" Choose Sound Player " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer} option from the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.

Personal sound files are accessed by clicking on the @{" Play Sound File " LINK PlaySound}
gadget in the Personal Details Window, and family sound files are accessed
by clicking on the @{" Play Sound File " LINK PlaySound} gadget in the Family Details Window.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK Hints and Tips help **************************************************

##
## "Hints, Tips & Questions"
##

@NODE Hints "Hints, Tips & Questions"
			   SOME COMMON QUESTIONS

WHAT IS THE BEST WAY TO SET ABOUT CREATING MY DATABASE?

      Refer to @{" Programme Overview " LINK Overview}


HOW DO I MARRY A PERSON MORE THAN ONCE?
      Establish the first marriage for the person by clicking on the
      @{" Set 1st Marriage " LINK SetMarriage} gadget in the Personal Details Window for
      that person. This will place you in the first Family Details Window
      with that person as "Principal".

      To create another marriage for that Principal, click on the
      @{" New Marriage " LINK NewMarriage} gadget in the Family Details Window. You will be
      asked if you want to create a new family group for that Principal.
      Answer "yes" and continue as you did for the first marriage by first
      adding a new Spouse (for the second marriage) and then adding the
      children of the second marriage.


HOW DO I MAKE THE "SPOUSE" IN A FAMILY DETAILS WINDOW INTO THE "PRINCIPAL"?
      Click on the @{" Exchange " LINK Exchange} gadget in the Family Details window.


HOW DO I CHANGE THE SPOUSE IN A FAMILY GROUP TO A DIFFERENT PERSON?
      From the appropriate Family Details Window, click on the
      @{" Set Spouse " LINK AddSpouse} gadget. You will be asked if you wish to remove
      the existing spouse and (optionally) replace with a new spouse.

      Answer "yes".

      You will then be presented with a list of the people currently in
      the database. Click on the name of the person that you wish to be
      the new spouse.

HOW DO I DELETE A SPOUSE FROM A FAMILY GROUP?
      From the appropriate Family Details Window, click on the
      @{" Set Spouse " LINK AddSpouse} gadget. You will be asked if you wish to remove
      the existing spouse and (optionally) replace with a new spouse.

      Answer "yes".

      At this point the existing spouse will be removed, and you will be
      presented with a list of the people currently in the database. Click
      on the "Cancel" gadget at the bottom of the list. The original
      spouse has now been removed from the family group.

      NOTE: If you need to re-instate the original spouse to the family
	    group, click on the "Set Spouse" gadget again and add
	    them (from the displayed list) to the family group.


WHAT ARE THE UNDERLINED DATES IN THE ON-SCREEN LISTS?
      For "people" lists, in the "birth" column, underlined dates represent
      BAPTISM dates (used in the absence of a birth date), and in the
      "death" column, underlined dates represent BURIAL dates (used in the
      absence of a death date).

      For "family" lists, in the "married" column, underlined dates
      represent ENGAGEMENT dates (used in the absence of a marriage date).


GREAT-AUNT ANN DIED ON CHRISTMAS DAY, BUT WE DON'T KNOW WHAT YEAR. HOW
DO I HANDLE SUCH DATES?
      Because "no-year" dates are not permitted in Scion, either estimate a
      year and mark the date as 'circa', or record the date in the
      'comments' field.


WHEN I PRINT REPORTS, I KEEP GETTING BLANK PAGES BETWEEN EACH REPORT PAGE.
      In the Workbench "Prefs/Printer" programme, decrease the "Paper
      Length" by 1 or 2. What is happening is that both Scion AND the
      printer are ejecting the paper at the end of the page. By
      reducing the preferences paper length, you are preventing the
      printer from ejecting the paper, and relying on Scion to do that
      function.


MY PEDIGREE CHART PRINTOUTS SOMETIMES PRINT PAST THE BOTTOM OF THE PAGE.
      In the Workbench "Prefs/Printer" programme, change the "Print
      Spacing" to '8 lines per inch'. Unfortunately Scion is unable to
      determine the length of the chart prior to printing. This errant
      behaviour will only occur when there is a substantial amount of
      information recorded for every person on the chart.


HOW DO I PRINT REPORTS TO A DISK FILE RATHER THAN TO THE PRINTER?
      Make sure that one of the  "Print to file" options under the
      @{" Set Print Options " LINK PrintPrefsReq} item of the "Print" menu is checked.


HOW DO I PRINT THE FREE-FORM NOTES I HAVE CREATED?
      Use the "Attach note..." option under the "Extras" menu, and tick
      "Print attached note" in the "Set print options" requester accessed
      from the "Print" menu. The notes file will then be automatically
      appended to either the Personal Summary report (for a personal note)
      or the Family Group Sheet report (for a family note).

      See also @{" Attachments " LINK Attachments}.


I DON'T SEE THE RIGHT-HAND SIDE OF MY REPORTS WHEN THEY ARE PRINTED TO
THE SCREEN. WHAT'S WRONG?
      The in-built text (notes) viewer in Scion does not perform word-
      wrapping, and you have set your Workbench printer preferences to
      a page width greater than the width of the screen.

      Either choose another notes viewer that either word-wraps or can
      show more characters per line, use the Workbench "Prefs/Printer"
      programme to reduce the width of the reports, or use the Workbench
      "Prefs/Font" programme and select a "System Default Font" that is
      narrower than the one currently in use. The Scion text viewer will
      attempt to use this system font for its display.

      See also @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}.


I DON'T SEE THE RIGHT-HAND SIDE OF MY NOTES FILES WHEN VIEWING THEM.
WHAT'S WRONG?
      The in-built text (notes) viewer in Scion does not perform word-
      wrapping. Either choose another notes viewer that either word-wraps
      or can show more characters per line, or use the Workbench
      "Prefs/Font" programme and select a "System Default Font" that is
      narrower than the one currently in use. The Scion text viewer will
      attempt to use this system font for its display.

      See also @{" Choose Notes Viewer " LINK ChooseNotesViewer}.


WHAT ARE THE SMALL BLACK DOTS TO THE RIGHT OF THE "EDIT/VIEW NOTES",
"VIEW PICTURE" AND "PLAY SOUND FILE" GADGETS?
      These black dots indicate that there are @{" attachments " LINK Attachments} defined for
      the currently displayed person or family.


NOW THAT SEPARATE "PREFERENCES" FILES ARE NO LONGER SUPPORTED, HOW CAN I
HAVE A SELECTION OF DIFFERENT SETTINGS?
      - Start Scion but do NOT load any database.
      - Set the settings preferences to whatever you want (remember you can
        import them from an existing version 5 database).
      - Save the database to your preferred location on disk. This saves a
        very small database file containing ONLY your preferred settings.
      - Repeat for as many different settings files as you want.
      - You can now "import" the settings from any of these files.
      See also @{" Import Settings " link ImportPrefs}.


HOW DO I ASSIGN A NAME TO MY DATABASE?
      When you select the @{" Save As... " LINK MenuSave} item from the @{" Project " LINK ProjectMenu} menu you are
      presented with a file requester. Simply type the new name for your
      database in the box near the bottom of the requester. The name of
      the database will also be used as a "suffix" for your free form
      notes and picture files.

      NOTE: It is strongly recommended that you "name" your database as
	    soon as you start working on it. For example, add one person
	    to the database and then save the database with a suitable
	    name. This will then establish its name (for notes, etc).


I TRY TO LOAD MY DATABASE FILE AND NOTHING HAPPENS!
      It probably means that your database file is too big for the
      remaining memory in your computer. Either:

      (1) you created the database on a computer with more memory, in
	  which case you will need to continue with the other computer
	  or buy more memory, or

      (2) you have one or more other application programmes running at
	  the moment, in which case you should close them down to free
	  up some memory.


WHEN I CLICK ON ONE OF THE "VIEW/EDIT NOTES" GADGETS, ALL I GET IS A
BRIEF FLASH OF THE WORKBENCH SCREEN?
      Either:

      (1) your specified viewer/editor is not available (have you removed
	  the disk, where it is located, from your disk drive?), or

      (2) you do not have enough memory left to run the viewer/editor, or

      (3) your chosen viewer/editor will not run from this environment
	  (try using a different viewer/editor). @{" Tested Editors " LINK TestedEditors}


WHEN I CLICK ON ONE OF THE "VIEW PICTURE" GADGETS, ALL I GET IS A BRIEF
FLASH OF THE WORKBENCH SCREEN?
      Either:

      (1) the picture file you have specified does not exist, or

      (2) your specified picture viewer is not available (have you
	  removed the disk, where it is located, from your disk drive?),
	  or

      (3) you do not have enough memory left to run the picture viewer
	  (try using a different viewer), or

      (4) your chosen picture viewer will not run from this environment, or

      (5) the format of the selected picture cannot be displayed by the
          chosen (or internal) picture viewer.


WHEN I CLICK ON ONE OF THE "PLAY SOUND FILE" GADGETS, ALL I GET IS A
BRIEF FLASH OF THE WORKBENCH SCREEN?
      Either:

      (1) the sound file you have specified does not exist, or

      (2) your specified sound file player is not available (have you
	  removed the disk, where it is located, from your disk drive?),
	  or

      (3) you do not have enough memory left to run the sound file player
	  (try using a different player), or

      (4) your chosen sound file player will not run from this environment.


WHEN I PLAY A SOUND FILE, ALL I GET IS A DREADFUL NOISE OR A FLASH OF THE
SCION SCREEN.
      The most likely cause is that the sound file is of the wrong format.

      There are many sound formats available for the Amiga. Scion's
      internal player will only play IFF-8SVX files. If your files are of
      a different format, select another sound player that supports your
      file format.

      See the @{" Choose Sound Player " LINK ChooseSoundPlayer} option under the @{" Settings " LINK PrefsMenu} menu.


WHEN I TRY TO USE THE EDITOR, VIEWER OR SOUND PLAYER I GET "Error 103
detected" MESSAGES. I HAVE PLENTY OF FREE MEMORY, SO WHY THE ERROR?
      You have probably 'launched' Scion Genealogist via one of the
      utility 'launching' programmes such as "AmiDock", "ToolsDaemon",
      or "ToolsManager" with Scion Genealogist specified as a 'CLI'
      type of programme.

      These 'launching' programmes require you to specify whether the
      programme you wish to launch is a "CLI" or "Workbench" type of
      programme. To eliminate these "Error 103 detected" messages when
      using one of these 'launching' programmes, make sure you specify
      Scion Genealogist as a "Workbench" type programme.


WHEN I TRY TO USE ANOTHER PROGRAMME IT OPENS ON THE SCION SCREEN. I WOULD
PREFER TO USE IT ON THE WORKBENCH SCREEN
      By default, the Scion screen is the "default public screen". This
      means that any programmes you start AFTER Scion will attempt to
      open on the Scion screen. Go to the @{" Set Behaviour " LINK SetBehaviour} requester
      and turn off the "Scion default public screen", "Shanghai windows"
      and "Pop screen to front" options.


WHAT ARE THE FILES NAMED "PN1.unnamed", "FN1.unnamed", ETC. THAT I
FIND IN MY DATABASE DIRECTORY (DRAWER)?
      You have created free form notes without first naming the database.
      Refer to @{" Edit Personal Notes " LINK PersonEditor} and @{" Edit Family Notes " LINK FamilyEditor}


HOW DO I QUICKLY MOVE FROM PERSON TO PERSON WHERE ALL THE PEOPLE OF
INTEREST HAVE THE SAME LAST NAME?
      Click on "Personal Search" gadget, and enter the last name in which
      you are interested into the Last Name field of the requester. Click
      on "Find First", "Find Next" or "Find Prev" to locate the next
      person.

      NOTE: This same technique may be used to "browse" families.

      Click on "Cancel" once you have located the person or family you
      are looking for.

THE "DESCENDANT CHART" REPORT ONLY SHOWS THE NAMES OF DESCENDANTS. I WANT
MORE DETAILS.
      Th descendant chart is a "summary" chart showing only the names of
      descendants. For complete details of all descendants, use the
      @{" Print Progeny Chart " LINK PrintProgeny} option.

@ENDNODE

##
## "LDS Compatibility"
##

@NODE LDS "LDS Compatibility"
                         LDS Compatibility

The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (LDS for short), requires
that additional information particular to that church be recorded.

This version of Scion does not support this additional information
explicitly. The "comments" or "references" fields can be used to record
this additional LDS information.
@ENDNODE

##
## "GEDCOM Support"
##

@NODE GEDCOM "GEDCOM Support"
                           GEDCOM Support

Scion can export and import GEDCOM data by way of ARexx scripts. Two such
scripts are supplied, "Scion2GEDCOM.rexx" and "GEDCOM2Scion.rexx",
written by Freddy Ariļs of the Netherlands.

Scion2GEDCOM will export GEDCOM data from a Scion database, and
GEDCOM2Scion will import GEDCOM data into a Scion database.

These ARexx scripts can either be run from a "shell" (once Scion is
running), or can be assigned to one of the user-defined function keys.
See @{" Set Function Keys " LINK SetFunctionKeys}.

For example, you might define "F1" to be "rx REXX:Scion2GEDCOM" and
"F2" to be "rx REXX:GEDCOM2Scion" (when the ARexx scripts are in the
"REXX:" location). If these Arexx scripts are in a different location,
replace "REXX:" with the location of the scripts. Now when "F1" is pressed,
the Scion2GEDCOM ARexx script will be executed from within Scion, etc.

See also the "ReadMe" file supplied with the ARexx scripts.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Tested Editors"
##

@NODE TestedEditors "Tested Editors"
Please remember, if you wish to print your notes as "attachments" to
printed reports that the notes MUST be created with a text editor, NOT
a word processor. If you create notes with a word processor, they must
either be printed from within that word processor or saved in standard
ASCII (text) format. Scion has no knowledge of the file formats produced
by word processors.

The following editors have been tested for compatibility with Scion
Genealogist:

These DO work:

1: "Mg2a" (formerly MicroGnuEmacs) Text Editor. Copyright various

2: "Mg3a" (formerly MicroGnuEmacs) Text Editor. Copyright various

3: "MicroEMACS" V2.1 Text Editor. Copyright ® 1986 by Commodore-Amiga, Inc.
    (Authors David Conroy & Andy Finkel). Supplied with Amiga computer

4: "Scribble!" V2.00 Word Processor. Copyright ® by Micro-Systems Software
    (Save files in ASCII format)

5: "TurboText" Text Editor. Copyright ® 1991 by Martin Taillefer

6: "MicroEMACS" V3.9 Text Editor. Copyright ® 1987 by David M Lawrence

7: "CygnusEd Professional" Text Editor. Copyright ® by CygnusSoft Software

8: "VizaWrite" Word Processor. Copyright ® Viza Software
    (Save files in ASCII format)

9: "Excellence!" Word Processor. Copyright ® by Micro-Systems Software
    (Save files in ASCII format)

10:"Ed" V2.0 Text Editor. Copyright ® 1991 by Commodore-Amiga, Inc.
    (Authors David Conroy & Andy Finkel). Supplied with Amiga computer

11:"Final Copy II". Copyright ® by Softwood Inc.
    (Save files in ASCII format)

12:"DME". Copyright ® by Mathew Dillon.

13:"PageLiner". Copyright ® by Soft-Logik Publishing Corp.
    (Save files in ASCII format)

14:"Articel Editor". Copyright ® by Gold disk.

    My thanks to Peter Billing of Yinnar, Australia, for supplying me with
    "compatibility" information for numbers 11 - 14 inclusive.

15: "FinalWriter". Copyright ® by Softwood Inc.
    (Save files in ASCII format)

These do NOT work:

1: "QED" V1.0 Text Editor. Copyright ® 1989 by Darren M. Greenwald

2: "Text Plus" V3.0 Text Editor. Copyright ® by Martin Steppler

3: "WordPerfect" Word Processor. Copyright ® by WordPerfect Corporation

4: "Textra" V1.13 Text Editor. Copyright ® 1993 by Mike Haas
@ENDNODE

##
## "Programme Specification"
##

@NODE Specification "Programme Specification"
                  Programme Specification and Requirements

Database stored in RAM for maximum speed. Memory usage typically 50% less
than earlier versions of Scion.

Works with floppy and/or hard-disk drives, but a hard-disk drive is
STRONGLY recommended.

Loads databases created with any earlier version of Scion or "ArJay
Genealogist".

Maximum number of people per database = limited only by available memory
Maximum number of families per database = limited only by available memory
Maximum number of marriages per person = 10
Maximum number of children per family group = 40

REQUIREMENTS:

	A minimum of 1 Mbyte of RAM is required. 4 Mbytes of RAM is
	recommended.

        Scion will use any "virtual" memory allocated by virtual memory
	managers such as GigaMem (® Copyright 1991,1992 Christian A
	Schnedier, F Burgel, Relog AG) and VMM (® Copyright 1994 Martin
	Apel).

	Kickstart/Workbench v2.04 (or later) required. Version 2.10 (or
        later) required for locale support (alternative languages).

	Any preferences supported printer.

SEE ALSO @{" What's New " LINK WhatsNew}.
@ENDNODE

##
## "Credits"
##

@NODE Credits "Credits"
  ________________________________________________________________________

                           Scion Genealogist
  ________________________________________________________________________

  Scion Genealogist is a genealogical database programme for managing
  information about your "family tree" and printing a variety of reports.

  The programme is FULLY FUNCTIONAL and is NOT disabled in any way.

  This programme is FREEWARE and is NOT to be sold (although a nominal
  charge may be made for copying). If you would would like to make a
  contribution to its author, or report on any bugs or suggested
  enhancements, please address any correspondence to:

                            Robbie J Akins
	                    5 Austin Street
			    Wellington 6001
			    NEW ZEALAND

			    EMAIL: rakins@bclnz.co.nz

  Particular thanks go to Freddy Ariļs of the Netherlands for his
  enthusiastic support, testing, suggestions, translations, and major
  ARexx support programmes which have helped to make Scion the success
